<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Residents Enjoy Better Housing Conditions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The per-capita living
space in Shanghai has grown by 29.6 percent to 8.7 sq.m. over the
past six years, according to information released during a local
symposium on housing finance.
</P>
<P>
Today's symposium was sponsored by the local branches of the
People's Bank of China and the China Construction Bank, and Morgen
Stanley Asia Ltd. of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government of Shanghai has extended great efforts
to improve the living conditions of local residents in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, Shanghai has allocated 127.78 billion yuan to
construct residential housing. New apartments with a total floor
space of 52.89 million square meters have been completed.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government has also reformed the
housing rental fees. A government plan calls for rental fees to
grow by some 50 percent annually during the Ninth Five-Year Plan
period (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, local families are expected to spend 15
percent of their annual income on rents.
</P>
<P>
Local residents are currently being encouraged to purchase
publicly-owned apartments.
</P>
<P>
By the end of October this year, some 670,000 local residents
had purchased publicly-owned housing in which they were living at
cost prices. Related housing covered 35 million sq.m. and
constituted some 54 percent of publicly-owned apartments on the
market.
</P>
<P>
The city introduced the system of public housing funds for
employees in 1991, with some 98 percent of local workers having
since participated in the program.
</P>
<P>
The fund has accumulated 16.49 billion yuan, with 13.82 billion
yuan allocated as housing loans enabling individuals to purchase
their own houses on the market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
