<HEADLINE> Six British Farmers Arrested After Beef Imports Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Six farmers were arrested Monday
after a truck was damaged in an incident which police believed to
have links with farmer's protests.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said around 100 people protested at the port of
Fishguard in Pembrokeshire Monday morning as part of the
continuing protests against cheap beef imports from Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Police said all vehicles left the port safely. But one was
stopped later near Haverfordwest with its rear lights broken.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in several port cities have staged protests since last
Monday against cheap beef imports. They even brockade roads to
ports with tractors to halt traffic.
</P>
<P>
The long-running "mad cow" disease crisis has hit the British
beef industry hard, and farmers have accused the government of not
doing enough to help them.
</P>
<P>
They were further angered on Wednesday when Secretary of State
for Agriculture, Jack Cunningham, proposed a ban on beef sold to
prevent a tiny risk that people may become infected with the human
form of mad cow disease, Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD).
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Tony Blair has urged the farmers to stop
blockading roads and ports, and vowed that law and order must be
upheld and truck routes must be kept open. 
</P>
</TEXT>
