<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cook: Long Way to Go in Achieving Lasting Bosnia Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 8 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook said here today there is still a long way to go in achieving
a lasting peace in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of an international conference due to open in Bonn,
Germany on Tuesday, Cook wrote in The Times newspaper today: "We
have a long way to go," although a series of achievements have
been made over the past two years since the Dayton Peace Agreement
was signed.
</P>
<P>
"Bosnia barely functions as a nation, let alone one able to
deal on equal terms with democracies in Europe," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Cook criticized Bosnian leaders in failing to restore their
shattered country by saying: "The efforts of the international
community can not make up for the inactivity of Bosnia's leaders."
</P>
<P>
"My main hope for Bonn (conference) is that it will issue a
wake-up call for Bosnia's leaders. Too often they have been
prepared to make progress only grudgingly, prodded into action by
the international community," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
"They must now live up their responsibility to lead the Bosnian
people into the real world," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Secretary also noted that the Bonn conference would
focus on human rights, open and fair government, transparency in
public finances and a free and independent media.
</P>
<P>
On the international peacekeeping mission in Bosnia, Cook said
that British Prime Minister Tony Blair has already made it clear
that British peacekeepers "should stay in the foreseeable future."
</P>
<P>
"We are in no doubt that a successor force to SFOR (Salvation
Force), whose mandate expires next June, must be NATO led with the
participation of all key allies" he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
