<HEADLINE> Hun Sen Meets With Prominent Government Critic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Second Prime
Minister Hun Sen held talks with opposition leader Sam Rainsy here
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
This is their first encounter since the end of 1994.
</P>
<P>
They did not release the contents of their hours-long talks,
which might have significant impact on the fate of the country.
</P>
<P>
"We have agreed, what is important is the national interest,"
Sam Rainsy said.
</P>
<P>
Sam Rainsy is a political ally of the deposed Prince Norodom
Ranariddh, who was ousted by Hun Sen in early July.
</P>
<P>
He served as finance minister for a year in the coalition
government set up by Ranariddh and Hun Sen after U.N.-run
elections in 1993 and was sacked in October 1994.
</P>
<P>
Both Sam Rainsy and Ranariddh were not in Cambodia at the time
of the prince's ouster and together they launched a campaign
against Hun Sen's new government from abroad.
</P>
<P>
But Sam Rainsy returned to Phnom Penh late last month and said
he would co-operate with the government to ensure that the 1998
election is free and fair. 
</P>
</TEXT>
