<HEADLINE> Ruehe's Resignation Urged for Neo-Nazi Army Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Germany's main opposition Social
Democrats (SPD) today demanded that Defense Minister Volker Ruehe
resign after another neo-Nazi scandal involving the German armed
forces being recently discovered.
</P>
<P>
Chancellor Helmut Kohl must consider sacking Ruehe in order to
show, once and for all, that the German army is not a neo-Nazi
playground, said SPD parliamentarian Hans Buettner.
</P>
<P>
In reply, Kohl said that he had full confidence in Ruehe.
</P>
<P>
Ruehe has vowed to drive all proven rightests out of the
Bundeswehr after many neo-Nazi incidents in the army went public,
such as drunken soldiers beating foreigners and homemade films
showing solders giving stiff-armed Hitler salute and mocking
executions and rapes.
</P>
<P>
Most recently, Ruehe admitted that Manfred Roeder, a leading
neo-Nazi, gave a lecture at the Hamburg Bundeswehr Leadership
Academy in 1995, on how to repopulate the former German state of
East Prussia, which was divided between Poland and Russia after
World War II, with ethnic Germans from the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
Roeder, 68, was convicted in 1982 of carrying out bomb attacks
on behalf of the rightist "German Action Group" and sentenced to
13 years in prison. He was released on probation in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The academy officials said that they were unaware of Roeder's
background when they invited him.  
</P>
</TEXT>
