<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slow Inflow of Foreign Capital in Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Trying its best since 1990,
Mongolia so far has contracted 164 million U.S. dollars worth of
foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
Seven years after it had a law to boost capital inflow, the
Bureau of Foreign Investment said today, the land-locked country
now hosts 708 joint or foreign ventures.
</P>
<P>
The foreign funds, the government agency said, mainly go into
Mongolia's oil, mining, livestock products, food and light
industries as well as its trade and service sectors.
</P>
<P>
Of the 26 million dollars capital inflow so far this year, 6
million dollars was in the mining industry and 7 million in the
trade and service sectors.
</P>
<P>
Those bringing much needed investments are from Japan, Russia,
China, Portugal and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Besides the preferential policies effective from 1990, Mongolia
is amending laws and regulations, and improving infrastructure to
make the country a better choice for investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
