<HEADLINE> Chretien Vows Quebec Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Canada's federal government
would negotiate with Quebec if the Yes forces won a referendum on
sovereignty there, said Prime Minister Jean Chretien.
</P>
<P>
The comment was the most clear-cut statement Chretien has made
that he would enter into talks on Quebec independence after an
indisputable vote for sovereignty in the French-speaking province.
</P>
<P>
"In situation like that, there will be a negotiation with the
federal government. No doubt about it. No doubt about it,"
Chretien was quoted as saying by reports today.
</P>
<P>
But the prime minister said that he's sure a unilateral
declaration of independence by Quebec would be illegal and "very
rare."
</P>
<P>
Conditions would have to be met before the federal government
agreed to negotiate, Chretien said at the end of the biennial
meeting of his Liberal Party's Quebec wing.
</P>
<P>
"But if, if, if," he added. "In theory there will be. But they
have to have a referendum, a clear question, a strong majority and
many other barriers to overcome," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Quebec Premier Lucien Bouchard and his Parti Quebecois
government have insisted that Quebec doesn't need anyone's
approval or permission to determine its future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
