<HEADLINE> Anti-smoking Position Not to Change, Chretien </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien said his government will not further reassess its
anti-smoking legislation in spite of pressure from the tobacco
industry.
</P>
<P>
"For us, the health question is fundamental," Chretien was
quoted as saying by today's Globe and Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The government has already decided to loosen the anti-smoking
Bill C-71 in certain areas.
</P>
<P>
"But we have no intention of abolishing the law," the Canadian
prime minister insisted.
</P>
<P>
"We believe (tobacco) is a major problem and that we have to
spend efforts to ensure that children do not fall into tobacco
trap," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chretien was responding to Imperial Tobacco's announcement
Friday that it will withdraw financial support for Canada's
cultural and sporting events by next October.
</P>
<P>
Bill C-71 limits the ability of tobacco companies to promote
themselves at arts and sporting events.
</P>
<P>
For example, it will restrict tobacco brand names to a
10-percent strip along the bottom of promotional signs or posters.
</P>
<P>
The bill was passed into law in April. As a result of intensive
lobbying by the tobacco industry, the government has agreed to
delay the sponsorship restriction to October 1, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
