<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> low world metal prices worrying in zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The current recession in metal
prices on the world market may threaten the operations and
viability of Zimbabwe's small mines, a senior Chamber of Mines
official said today.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive of the Chamber Derek Bain said the fall in
mineral prices was also likely to significantly reduce profits in
the bigger companies which would be forced to scale down
operations.
</P>
<P>
''the more profitable companies may have to take cost cutting
measures which may include retrenchments while those companies
which make marginal profits will face closure if the situation
does not improve,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
The plummeting metal prices have caused panic in local and
international mining concerns as several companies have recorded
losses and reduced profits.
</P>
<P>
Minerals most affected include gold, nickel, copper and
ferrochrome.
</P>
<P>
Prices for gold, the country's second biggest single forex
earner after tobacco are currently hovering at around 220 U.S.
Dollars per ounce, a big drop from the 400 US Dollars per ounce
that is considered as the good price.
</P>
<P>
On recent suggestions that Southern Africa Development
Community (SADC) countries should form cartel to be able to
influence prices on the world market, Bain said although it was a
good idea, the total regional mineral output was not enough to
influence the fixing of prices.
</P>
<P>
He added, ''the formation of such cartel would be against
certain provisions of the world trade organization (WTO ) and
furthermore the output may not be big enough to influence
prices."
</P>
<P>
"We can only hope that prices will improve soon,'' he noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
