<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Train Police Force for Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 8 (Xinhua) -- A visiting delegation from the
Democratic Republic of Congo (former Zaire) announced here today
that the country was to engage Zimbabwe in training its police
force.
</P>
<P>
Pascal Baruku Alimasi, head of the delegation and
director-general for Congolese police, said the central African
country would discuss areas of possible collaboration with
Zimbabwe during the week-long visit in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Zimbabwe is the first country that we came to for support
because it has an experienced police force," said Baruku Alimasi.
</P>
<P>
According to him, areas for bilateral cooperation include
general training and improving basic education in the police
force.
</P>
<P>
"We have a problem of equipment which must be used by the
police and we are hoping that Zimbabwe can help us," Alimasi
said.
</P>
<P>
The eight-man delegation is expected to confer with Zimbabwe's
Home Affairs Minister Dumiso Dabengwa later this afternoon and
tour various departments of the Zimbabwean police force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
