<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Industries Operate at Near-Peak Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Canada's industries operated at
86.2 percent of capacity in the third quarter of 1997, Statistics
Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
Propelled by high foreign demand, strong business and consumer
spending, the industries produced goods at an operating level just
shy of its peak recorded in the 1988 economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
"Rates of capacity use have been rising for over a year and are
now at or near recorded levels," the federal statistics agency
said.
</P>
<P>
An industry's capacity use is the ratio of its actual output to
its estimated potential output.
</P>
<P>
In the third quarter, 14 of the country's 22 industry groups
raised their rates of capacity use, and eight of them recorded
rates over 90 percent, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
However, "there is still no evidence of inflation in the
economy," it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
