<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Representative Explains Policy on Climate Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 8 (Xinhua) -- China opposes the introduction of
any new commitments by the developing countries in addressing
global warming, a senior Chinese official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Chen Yaobang, Chinese forestry minister and head of the Chinese
delegation, made the remark in a speech to the delegates from some
160 nations at the ministerial session of the U.N. climate change
conference in Kyoto, western Japan.
</P>
<P>
"China supports the adoption of a protocol or another legal
instrument that is in conformity with the U.N. Framework
Convention on Climate Change and the `Berlin Mandate'," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
However, China "is opposed to the introduction of any new
commitments for the developing countries and the launching of any
negotiation process that attempts to introduce new commitments for
developing countries," he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Framework Convention on Climate Change, adopted five
years ago, set forth different commitments for developed countries
and developing countries in combating climate change in accordance
with the principles of "common but differentiated
responsibilities" and equity, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, though the implementation of the
Convention has been on track, its progress has fallen short of
expectations.
</P>
<P>
This is mainly because most of the developed countries will not
be able to fulfil their commitments in stabilizing their
anthropogenic emissions of greenhouse gases at their 1990 levels
by the end of this century, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that although the Convention stipulates that the
developed countries should provide financial resources and
technology needed by the developing countries to implement the
Convention, there is no progress in technology transfer.
</P>
<P>
All this shows that the implementation of the Convention is
faced with great challenges.
</P>
<P>
Chen also expressed disappointment with the failure of the
developed countries to take the lead in combating climate change
as stipulated by the "Berlin Mandate", which was adopted two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
On China's policies on tackling global warming, Chen said the
Chinese government attaches great importance to the issue of
global climate, adding that China is among the 10 leading
countries that have ratified the Convention.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has formulated "China's Agenda 21", a
sustainable development strategy which is suited to China's
country-specific conditions, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has set up a Co-ordinating Group on
Climate, involving all relevant ministries and departments, and
has taken climate change into consideration in programming
socio-economic development.
</P>
<P>
In the past 20 years, China has made great contribution to
modifying longer-term trends of climate change by persevering in
large-scale afforestation and implementing policy of controlling
population growth, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
As a developing country with 1.2 billion people, while being
willing to make greater contribution to addressing climate change,
China is also faced with enormous actual difficulties in this
regard, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Chen unveiled four aspects in which China will make efforts to
tackle climate change such as persisting in controlling the
population growth rate, encouraging and popularizing energy saving
technologies, and developing renewable energies.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese minister also said that China is ready to take an
active role in international cooperation and exchanges and to make
due share of contribution in addressing climate change within the
framework of the Convention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
