<HEADLINE> Georgian President on Border Problem with Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Georgian President Eduard
Shevardnadze Monday expressed confidence in settling the border
dispute between his country and Russia through negotiations, the
Itar-Tass News Agency reported from Tbilisi.
</P>
<P>
There can be no problems or strategic contradictions insoluble
between the two countries, Shevardnadze said, adding that he and
his Russian counterpart Boris Yeltsin have created a legal basis
for solving the border issue.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, a Russian delegation headed by Deputy
Prime Minister Valery Serov is expected to arrive Tbilisi on
Monday, and to talk, among other problems in bilateral relations,
the border issue.
</P>
<P>
Shevardnadze said the Georgian side is ready to resume
negotiations with Russia.
</P>
<P>
The Tbilisi government had earlier accused Russian border
guards of "unilaterally moving the border sign in an area where
the border has not been finally agreed upon", while Russian border
guards claimed moving the sign had not changed the existing border.
</P>
<P>
Shevardnadze said the Russian border guards "seized the agreed
1.5 kilometer-wide neutral zone without any talks or notification."
</P>
<P>
Delimitation and demarcation of the border, the Georgian
president pointed out, should be decided by state commissions of
the two countries. 
</P>
