<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine House Approves Tax Reform Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine House of
Representatives today finally approved the country's vital income
tax reform bill, the third and final phase of the Comprehensive
Tax Reform Package (CTRP).
</P>
<P>
The ratification was announced by House Speaker Jose de Venecia
this evening, who was just chosen by President Fidel Ramos as the
ruling Lakas party's presidential candidate for the 1998 polls.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which will help generate 7 billion pesos (200 million
U.S. dollars) in new revenues for the government, is a vital
requirement in the country's planned exit from 35 years of
economic supervision by the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The country was supposed to graduate from the last IMF
supervision program in June this year, but the graduation was
delayed due to the lower house's failure to pass the CTRP.
</P>
<P>
The lower house's passage of the income tax bill cleared the
last hurdle for the country's graduation from the IMF, which was
rescheduled for the end of this month. The Senate had already
approved the bill last month.
</P>
<P>
The income tax bill provides a 100 percent tax exemption to 4
million overseas Filipino workers (OFWs) and wide-ranging tax
breaks to 25 million workers at home.
</P>
<P>
"This is our gift to Philippine labor," said De Venecia,
beaming after mobilizing the ruling party's allies in the lower
house to successfully ensure the passage of the measure.
</P>
<P>
"This is for the OFWs who helped prop up the country,
especially during the dark days of its economy, and this is for
workers who stayed home and helped create the Philippine economic
miracle," De Venecia said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
