<HEADLINE> Luxembourg PM: Talk With All Those Willing to Enter EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Luxembourg Prime Minister
Jean-Claude Juncker said here Monday that talks should be held
with all those applying for the European Union (EU) membership.
</P>
<P>
However, Junker told a news conference joined by his Finnish
counterpart Paavo Lepponen, the pace of the negotiations should
vary according to each of the 11 countries' economic development.
</P>
<P>
His remarks were made after the two prime ministers'
discussion on the scenario for the EU's eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
The Luxembourg prime minister's new proposal was believed here
to be a compromise over the different views within the EU on how
to grant the membership to Central and Eastern European countries.
</P>
<P>
Lepponen said Finland is in favor of Luxembourg's proposal, and
called on the other 13 current members of the regional bloc to
reach a consensus in the accession talks scheduled for early 1998.
</P>
<P>
In addition, media reports here said Sweden, Denmark and Italy
also agree to talk with all applicants at the same time.
</P>
<P>
Besides the EU enlargement, the Luxembourg and Finnish
ministers also discussed the mechanism for consultation within the
European Monetary Union (EMU), and the presidency for the future
European Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
Juncker, who arrived here on Saturday evening, left afterwards
for Sweden and Denmark to continue his tour in the Nordic region.
</P>
</TEXT>
