<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Firms Not Prepared for Year 2000 Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Less than half of all Canadian
firms have taken action to prepare for anticipated Year 2000
computer problems, Statistics Canada said today.
</P>
<P>
As the clock tick away towards the January 1, 2000 deadline,
about 10 percent of all companies were not even aware of the
problem, the statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
A further 46 percent of all firms said they were aware of the
issue, but had not done anything about it.
</P>
<P>
The Year 2000 issue refers to the need to fix computers whose
programming assumes that every year begins with "19".
</P>
<P>
Unless they are updated, they will assume that the day
following December 31, 1999, is actually January 1, 1900. This
will cause great confusion to everything related to computers.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the problem could cost the Canadian
economy a minimum of 12 billion dollars (8.5 billion USD) in
direct costs to fix.
</P>
<P>
"This total excludes the unidentified costs of the many
businesses that have not begun to address the problem," the agency
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
