<HEADLINE> Cyprus Willing to Discuss Turkish Cypriots' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government is ready
to discuss the proposals on Turkish Cypriots' representation in
the European Union (EU) accession talks, a government spokesman
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, Manolis Christofides
noted that the EU recognizes the Cypriot government as the only
legitimate negotiator.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on the call by Turkish Cypriots and Turkey
for inclusion of Turkish Cypriot representatives in Cyprus'
delegation for EU accession talks.
</P>
<P>
All those interested in Turkish Cypriots' representation in
accession talks are expected to have some ideas to propose, he
noted, adding that "we are willing to discuss the issue when it
arises."
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that all proposals should comply with
U.N. resolutions against the recognition of the illegal entity
unilaterally declared by the Turkish Cypriots in the northern part
of the island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 a breakaway "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus," which was only recognized by
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether it will be tangible to start Cyprus-EU accession
talks on April 10, 1998, Christofides said Cyprus believes
negotiations will start on that date, even if the problem of
Turkish Cypriots' representation is not yet settled.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also announced that President Glafcos Clerides
will attend the Luxembourg meeting of members of the European
Council, European Commission and associated countries later this
week.
</P>
<P>
Clerides will then visit Luxembourg, currently holding the EU
six-month rotating presidency, at the invitation of the country's
Prime Minister Jean-Claude Juncker. 
</P>
</TEXT>
