<HEADLINE> France to Provide Food Aid to Ethiopia: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Visiting French Minister
of Cooperation Charles Josselin announced here today that France
will provide 10,000 tons of food aid to Ethiopia in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made when Josselin met with Ethiopian
Minister of Economic Development and Cooperation Girma Birru,
according to the Ethiopian News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The food aid will be given as Ethiopia has been hard hit by
the El Nino weather pattern. Dozens of people died in floods in
the eastern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the first general Franco-Ethiopian joint commission
meeting was held here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the meeting, Josselin said the opening of the
commission extends the Ethio-French cooperation to areas like
political dialogue as well as economic and commercial relations.
</P>
<P>
He said France could provide Ethiopia with the benefits of its
expertise and know-how in the legal cooperation and animal
husbandry in particular.
</P>
<P>
Josselin added that trade between France and Ethiopia has
increased by 50 percent within three years and France has
recently been the second largest foreign investor in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Girma said that the level of Ethio-French
cooperation is widening in the fields of culture, science,
education, politics and economy.
</P>
<P>
He said a number of projects including the rehabilitation of
the Ethio-Djibouti railway and supervision work for Tiss Abay
hydropower project are being implemented smoothly through the
collaborative efforts of the two governments.
</P>
<P>
Josselin today also met and held talks with Ethiopian Foreign
Minister Seyoum Mesfin on issues pertaining to bilateral
relations and the situation in central and east African
countries, according to a spokesman from the Ethiopian Foreign
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The governments of France and Ethiopia have signed here a
joint communique to extend the 1966 Ethio-French cultural,
scientific and technical agreement to include political and
economic issues.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the visiting French minister today visited the
United Nations Economic Commission for Africa (ECA) here and
signed an exchange of letters with the ECA.
</P>
<P>
The French minister ended his three-day visit here today.
</P>
</TEXT>
