<HEADLINE> WHO to Unite International Efforts Against Buruli Ulcer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) is trying to unite international efforts to fight against
Buruli ulcer in particular in Africa, WHO Director-General Dr
Hiroshi Nakajima announced.
</P>
<P>
"Today, on behalf of the World Health Organization, I can
announce to you that we have taken the decision to unite
international efforts for the control of this scourge," said
Nakajima on the occasion of his visit to Cote d'Ivoire. "We are
going to mobilize worldwide expertise and the necessary resources
for confronting this new challenge."
</P>
<P>
Buruli ulcer is a terrible disease mainly striking young
people. Cases have been reported since 1948 in Benin, Cote
d'Ivoire, Gabon, Ghana and Uganda, according to a WHO press
release here today.
</P>
<P>
A working group specially set up by WHO will be meeting for the
first time in 1998 to take stock of current knowledge about this
disease and propose a two-year plan of action.
</P>
<P>
Many questions remain unanswered regarding the agent of this
disease, the conditions of its survival in the natural environment
and its mechanisms of transmission to man.
</P>
<P>
Buruli ulcer seems on its way to replacing leprosy as a social
scourge in Cote d'Ivoire, where some 400 cases have been recorded
since 1978.
</P>
<P>
At present, there is no medical treatment for effectively
controlling Buruli ulcer, which is the third most widespread
mycobacterial disease in the world after tuberculosis and leprosy.
</P>
<P>
The only treatment possible consists in extensively excising
the lesion and making a skin graft, which is not only long and
costly but leaves sequelae.
</P>
<P>
The disease exists in the form of endemic foci in the marshy
parts of the tropical and subtropical regions of Asia, Oceania,
Latin America and Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somalis Threatened by Cholera Epidemic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Doctors in the Somali
capital have warned against the spread of cholera epidemic in the
wake of the rainy season.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference in Forlanini Hospital, north Mogadishu
today, the Joint Health Authority (JHA) warned against the
possibility of a large number of child mortality as a result of
cholera if the situation is not intervened promptly.
</P>
<P>
Dr Ibrahim Maow Gandi, acting coordinator for the JHA, said
they have so far recorded the death of 41 children in the past
few days alone while 721 other people, mainly children, are now
suffering from severe diarrhoea and cholera.
</P>
<P>
According to the doctor, six out of 13 samples taken from
these affected children tested positive of cholera in
laboratories in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
The JHA warned that without quarantines the disease will
further spread into new communities.
</P>
<P>
There are both chlorine and sodium infusions in some of the
warehouses of the aid agencies in Mogadishu, Gandi said, adding
however, "The local staff cannot do anything during the absence
of the international expatriates who fled the capital for
security related problems."
</P>
<P>
"We would suggest that the local staff are authorized to give
out some help," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The JHA called on the people to bring their patients to the
hospitals where they can at least get some medical help or
consultations. The sodium infusions are getting scarce as
diarrhoea and cholera are affecting the people, especially the
children, in the capital in their hundreds.
</P>
<P>
In the markets and chemist's, one bag of 0.5-liter infusion is
now sold in 20,000 Somali Shillings (about three U.S. Dollars),
which only a few people can afford. But earlier it was sold in
less than one Dollar.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, airlifted food have begun to reach flood affected
regions in southern Somalia. Reports from Buale town said two
helicopters have made four flights to their town dropping some
food.
</P>
<P>
Elders from the town said that planes belonging to the World
Food Program are yet to quench down the hunger of the people as
each flight brought about not enough supplies to combat the
suffering of tens of thousands of people who fled their houses
from the floods.
</P>
<P>
Both the floods and rains continue further to devastate
villages and towns. The local authority in Sablale district of
lower Shabelle region have declared the flood situation is now
out of hand.
</P>
<P>
Adan Farah Abdi, a community elder in Sablale, said all 27
villages around the town are now deserted due to the flood
waters, and the road linking the town to the capital is also cut
off.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of these people are now on the small flood created
islands without food, shelter and medicine. They are also dying
in dozens of malaria and famine, said the elders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
