<HEADLINE> Diplomats Call for Arab Common Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Senior Arab diplomats today
called for reviving the decades-old dream of creating an Arab
common market.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a cultural seminar on the Arab common market held
here, Fouad al Sadek al Mahdi, Saudi Arabia's representative to
the Arab League, called for the revival of Arab solidarity in an
effort to promote development and build strong economy.
</P>
<P>
He said to set up a common market among Arab countries is "an
urgent obligation."
</P>
<P>
The Arab League proposed to set up the Arab common market more
than 30 years ago, which still remains a dream today.
</P>
<P>
As a prelude to liberalize trade among Arab countries by 2007,
an Arab free trade area will be set up next year.
</P>
<P>
When complaining of the Arab underdevelopment, Syria's
Ambassador to Egypt Issa Darwish said one out of three in the Arab
workforce will be unemployed in the first decade of the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
He added that the inter-Arab investment currently amounts to
almost nothing when compared to Arab investment in other parts of
the world.
</P>
<P>
But he said the Arab world has a strong economic
potential. Egypt, Syria and the oil-rich Saudi Arabia will be the
center of Arab renaissance, he predicted.
</P>
<P>
The Arab world has 252 million population, 62 percent of
world's known oil reserves, 22 percent of natural gas reserves,
and produces 66 percent of world's oil annually.
</P>
<P>
The seminar organized by the Egyptian Committee of the
Afro-Asian Peoples Solidarity Organization was attended by Arab
diplomats, economists, media men and experts on Arab affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
