<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ILO/UNDP Report Sees Economic Revival in Sub-Saharan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Economy in sub-Saharan Africa is
showing the first signs of resurgence, with 33 countries enjoying
economic growth rates greater than the rate of increase in their
populations, according to a report made public here today.
</P>
<P>
"Africa has no alternative but to embark on a process of
sustained GDP growth if it is to avoid continued marginalization"
from the global economy, says Jobs for Africa, a new report by the
International Labor Organization (ILO) and United Nations
Development Program (UNDP).
</P>
<P>
The report points out that while recovery prospects can be
boosted by further domestic reforms and increased international
investment, accelerated job and income growth are now critical to
sustaining the upturn and maintaining political stability in what
has become the world's poorest region.
</P>
<P>
The overall economic growth rate in sub-Saharan Africa rose to
3.7 percent in 1995, the last year for which accurate figures are
available, up from 1.9 percent in 1994, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
"The turnaround in growth signals the beginning of a new start
in Africa if the right policies are put in place and pursued
consistently," said ILO economist Samir Radwan.
</P>
<P>
The report's main author believed that the main emphasis of
policy makers "should be on encouraging new, private-sector
enterprises, particularly those which are small in scale and labor
intensive, and on enabling small enterprises to expand, innovate
and penetrate new markets, including export markets".
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the report acknowledges that Africa's recent
reversal of fortune is still anaemic and highly vulnerable. It
cites "the development of productive employment" as one of the
potential stumbling blocks for the economic growth in the
sub-Saharan African region.
</P>
<P>
From 1978 to 1994, labor force in sub-Saharan Africa continued
to grow at about three percent annually, declining or stagnating
levels of wage employment, decreasing real wages and deteriorating
working and living conditions" throughout the region, according to
the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-08 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Criticizes Europe for Siding With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu today criticized some European countries for
automatically siding with the Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
over the stalemate in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu voiced the complaint at the weekly Cabinet meeting,
during which he briefed the cabinet on his just-concluded visit
last week to Europe, where he held talks with leaders of Germany,
France and United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
Both Germany and France criticized Israel for its
intransigience on the issue of further troop redeployments in the
West Bank, which have been long delayed in violation of the signed
agreements.
</P>
<P>
On last Thursday, German Chancellor Helmut Kohl reportedly
expressed to Netanyahu his "growing concern" over the peace
process when they met in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac made similar comments in his
Saturday meeting with Netanyahu in Paris, saying he is
pessimistic about the prospects of the peace. Chirac added that
long delays in the peace process are a threat to Israel's
security.
</P>
<P>
After hearing Netanyahu's proposal on the second redeployment,
both Kohl and Chirac stressed that the Israeli plan for further
pullback is insufficient. Although the Israeli government has
never publicized its plan on the redeployment, local media has
widely reported that Netanyahu is proposing a 6-8 percent
withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to some speculations, Netanyahu said he did not
discuss the extent of the second redeployment with Albright
during their two meetings last week in Paris.
</P>
<P>
He added, however, that he did tell Albright that the
PNA's initiative to achieve state status in the United Nations
was a violation of its commitments and the Oslo obligations.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister David Levy urged the cabinet to produce a
clear proposal on the further redeployment as soon as possible,
otherwise Netanyahu would not be able to hold another meeting
with Albright on December 17 in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
During her meetings with Netanyahu, Albright urged Israeli
government to approve a more credible further redeployment in
order to push forward the peace process. The U.S. government
is increasingly impatient with the slow pace in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, which have failed to achieve any
progress since their resumption early October after a seven-month
freeze.
</P>
<P>
Speaking today in Paris after meeting with French Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin, Albright said she believes both Israelis
and Palestinians are genuinely trying to advance the peace
process. She reiterated that Israel has to come up with a plan on
the second troop redeployment, while the PNA must fulfill its
obligations in the field of security by making 100 percent effort
to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The Netanyahu-led ministerial committee charged with deciding
the extent of further redeployment and guidelines on the
permanent talks has already held three meetings, but failed to
reach an agreement so far because of differences of opinions
on Israeli security interests.
</P>
<P>
The committee will not reconvene until its member, Defense
Minister Mordechai's scheduled return on Wednesday. Israeli
sources doubted if the committee will be able to finish drawing a
final map on the redeployment and permanent talks before next
week's meeting between Netanyahu and Albright. 
</P>
</TEXT>
