<HEADLINE> Ethiopians Enjoy Constitutional Rights: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopians are currently
undertaking various political, economic and social activities by
taking advantages of the different rights provided by the Federal
Constitution, President Negasso Gidada said today.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, Negasso made the
statement here in an opening speech to a human rights symposium
organized in connection with the third anniversary of the
adoption of the Federal Constitution.
</P>
<P>
By exercising these rights which entitle them to the right of
self determination up to secession, the president said, "the
people are deciding directly on all issues affecting their life
and involve themselves in their execution."
</P>
<P>
State accountability has also been ensured through the
creation of favorable conditions for the people to bring down
from power untrustworthy representatives, he added.
</P>
<P>
"On the whole, our constitution is a supreme law of the
country which ensures respect for basic human rights of
individuals and people which develops, in an organized manner,
the broad and democratic participation of the people," Negasso
noted.
</P>
<P>
"Clear signs are already emerging that the constitution
represents a strong popular expression capable of removing the
old outlook of territorial unity and replacing it by a popular
democratic unity founded on voluntary will of the people," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Dawit Yohannes, speaker of the House of People's
Representatives, said at the symposium that the house has already
registered satisfactory results in its day to day struggle to
translate the constitution into reality.
</P>
<P>
In addition to efforts aimed at building its capacity, the
house has conducted a detailed study of the five-year development
program presented to it by the executive branch, and had made it
its own and the nation's work plan, Yohannes noted.
</P>
<P>
"The constitution of the Federal Democratic Republic of
Ethiopia" was ratified on December 8, 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
