<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament Defeats Non-Confidence Motion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Knesset (Parliament)
today rejected a non-confidence motion against Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu by a vote of 52-45 with 2 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
The motion, which dealt with both political-diplomatic issues
and the country's economy, were filed by opposition Labor party,
left wing party Meretz, Hadash and the Democratic Arab Party.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Cabinet's decision on the further
redeployment in the West Bank, the motion charged that Netanyahu
has failed in advancing the Oslo peace process and there was
nothing new in the government decision.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Cabinet last month approved Netanyahu's proposal that
Israel implements further withdrawal from unspecified areas of
the West Bank on condition that Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) fulfills its commitments as appended to the Hebron
Agreement last January.
</P>
<P>
The motion also said that Netanyahu should be responsible for
the five-day crippling nationwide strike, launched by the Trade
Union last Wednesday in protest against government plans for
wages reform and privatization.
</P>
<P>
The strike caused heavy economic losses to the country by
effectively shutting down airports, seaports, banks, government
offices and state-owned industries. The Treasury put the economic
losses of the strike at some 300 million shekels (about 86 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Labor leader Ehud Barak has said that Netanyahu can not bring
about either peace or security to the country because he has lost
all credibility with the Palestinians, the United States and even
Knesset members and government ministers.
</P>
<P>
"Our stand is clear: we do not have confidence in Netanyahu and
we will vote against him in all non-confidence motions," Barak
said.
</P>
<P>
Barak also said he expects there will be general elections
next year and that the party is preparing for them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
