<HEADLINE> BA Takes Tough Measures to Curb Drunkenness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 8 (Xinhua) -- British Airways (BA) announced a
new "alcohol policy" to curb drunkenness by air travellers to
ensure the safety and security of passengers and staff, said local
press reports today.
</P>
<P>
Under the policy, BA employees will be empowered to prevent
passengers who appear drunk from boarding aircraft. They should
also stop serving in-flight alcohol to anyone who seems to be
drunk.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, crew members can confiscate duty-free drink from
drunken passengers, and the drink will be returned to passengers
once an aircraft has reached its destination.
</P>
<P>
The new measures followed two recent court cases which involved
assaults on airline cabin crew by drunken passengers.
</P>
<P>
BA said that as with most other air carriers, it is
experiencing an increase in the frequency and severity of
disruptive and drunken behavior by passengers, which places
+unacceptable burdens on crew members and ground staff.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that over the past year, 14 serious incidents
involving violence had been reported on BA's planes compared with
only two or three five years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
