<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The British government announced
here today that it would contribute an additional 720,000 pounds
(about 1.2 million U.S. dollars) in a new effort to support the
European Union (EU) Caribbean Drugs Initiative (CDI).
</P>
<P>
A British Foreign Office spokesman said in a statement issued
this afternoon that the Foreign Office will contribute 500,000
pounds (830,000 dollars) towards some CDI projects, which aimed at
the training of law enforcement officials and members of the
judiciary.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the British Home Office is separately providing
220,000 pounds (about 365,000 dollars) towards another project,
which is designed to intercept drugs being smuggled at sea, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
British Minister of State Tony Lloyd said today: "These
additional funds will provide a significant boost to the fight
against the drugs trade."
</P>
<P>
"Some 30 percent of the cocaine destined for the UK first
transits the Caribbean. British is determined to do everything it
can to substantially reduce this flow," Lloyd said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that British drugs-related assistance to the
Caribbean region totaled some 15 million pounds (about 25 million
dollars) over the past two years. 
</P>
