<HEADLINE> Nigeria Loses $125 Million Yearly on Timber </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Mismanagement of Nigeria's rich
wood resources has inflicted an annual loss of about 125 million
U.S. Dollars on the country's timber revenue, a United Nations
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
"The nation loses 10 billion Naira yearly because of the
continuous use of sawdust producing machines unlike in South
Africa, Europe and America," said Kehinde Sanwo, consultant on
tropical timber for the U.N. Food and Agricultural Organization,
according to the News Agency of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Ondo and Oyo states in southwestern Nigeria with the highest
concentration of rare species, account for 60-80 percent of the
country's timber revenue losses, noted Sanwo.
</P>
<P>
Another major cause for the loss of forest resources is
desertification, which eats five kilometers of land per year and
could be attributable to national "voracious" land hunger and
uncoordinated urbanization, the U.N. official said.
</P>
<P>
The wasteful use of international aid on deforestation and
degradation control by government agencies has led to the
stoppage of assistance, Sanwo added.
</P>
<P>
He also claimed that current assistance through private
companies were being marred by greed.
</P>
<P>
Only education and enhanced research in renewable resources
would help combat environmental degradation, the official
stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
