<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Some multi-million-U.S.-dollar
facilities constructed about 17 years ago in the new Nigerian
capital Abuja are now facing imminent threat of collapse if
urgent steps are not taken to salvage the situation.
</P>
<P>
The general condition of the facilities has deteriorated
drastically due to lack of routine maintenance and neglect by the
authorities, the News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
The facilities, according to the report, comprise sewage and
drainage systems, road networks as well as water and electricity
supply installations.
</P>
<P>
As part of the measure to improve the situation, the
Authorities of the Federal Capital Territory have mapped out key
areas to start rehabilitating and improving such facilities as
roads, water and electricity supply equipment, it said.
</P>
<P>
Abuja was created in 1976 because of the inadequacies of Lagos
in the southwest coast to function as the federal capital.
</P>
<P>
Located in the center of the country, the Federal Capital
Territory covers an area of about 8,000 square kilometers, which
is two and half times the size of Lagos state. 
