<HEADLINE> Israel's Labor Party Differs Over Peace Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Israel's Labor Party leader
Ehud Barak said here today that only formal decisions of the party
can represent its positions on the issues of Golan Heights and the
Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a meeting of top Labor officials in
response to a statement by Shimon Peres, former Labor leader and
prime minister of the Labor government, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
While praising Peres as a great statesman who has won the
respect of all party members, Barak said that it is the party as
an institution that decides the positions on such issues as Golan
Heights and Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at Labor convention held in Tel Aviv, Peres strongly
advocated a Palestinian state and the return of the Golan Heights
to Syria to realize a lasting and comprehensive peace.
</P>
<P>
"If we want a Jewish state, then we need to have a non-Jewish
state right alongside it, not just some vague entity. We need what
is explicitly and unequivocally a Palestinian state," said Peres.
</P>
<P>
He asserted that Syrian President Hafez al-Assad "wants peace,
but he won't make peace in return for only part of the Golan
Heights. If we put this off, the price (Israel has to pay) will
not decrease, not even in 10 years."
</P>
<P>
The Golan Heights, part of Syrian territory, was occupied by
Israel during the 1967 Six-day War.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, at the meeting of Labor's top officials, some key
members of the party criticized Barak for siding with the current
government of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and trying to
stage a "one man show" on the issues of the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Peres, a leading figure of Israel's former Labor government in
reaching the Oslo Accord with the Palestine Liberation
Organization in 1993, is a firm advocate of realizing peace with
the Arab neighbors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
