<HEADLINE> Greece's Position in NATO Upgraded, Says Tsohatzopoulos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos said today that Athens' position in the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) had been promoted after the
agreement last week on the alliance's new structure.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference today, Tsohatzopoulos said that
Greece had for the first time acquired the right of veto in the
alliance which Athens withdrew from in 1974 and rejoined in 1980.
</P>
<P>
He complained several days ago that for the past decades,
Greece had been regard as "a second-class member" because the
alliance's old structure allowed Turkey to use a veto on a series
of important issues.
</P>
<P>
Under NATO's new military structure, a headquarters will
function in Naples, Italy for NATO's southern flank, with one
regional subheadquarters in Greece, Italy, Spain and Turkey. The
subheadquarters in Larissa, Greece, will have a Greek commander
and 55 percent of its staff will all be Greek nationals.
</P>
<P>
Greece's participation in the new NATO structure, he said,
would promote the desired policies of security, stability and
cooperation in the greater region of the Balkans, trans-Caucasia
and the Black Sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
