<HEADLINE> Nigeria Chides Developed Nations over Climate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria today chided developed
countries for breach of faith and lack of leadership in providing
financial and technological commitment required to mitigate
climate change all over the world.
</P>
<P>
It then urged developed countries to commit themselves to
serious technology cooperation and redeem their financial pledges
without any conditionality.
</P>
<P>
These are the highlights of a speech at the ongoing World
Climate Change Conference in Tokyo today, delivered by Adegoke
Adegoroye, director-general of Nigeria's Federal Environmental
Protection Agency (FEPA).
</P>
<P>
Noting that an ad hoc group was set up in Berlin in 1995 to
embark on the negotiation of a protocol on world climate change,
the FEPA chief said the group had become necessary because some
developed countries had not demonstrated leadership.
</P>
<P>
"Eight sessions of the ad hoc group from Berlin to Tokyo, it
has yet to be proved to the international community that these
major developed countries are committed to the principles set
forth within the context of the framework Convention on Climate
Change," he said, quoted by the News Agency of Nigeria today.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria supported the establishment of a compensation fund
currently being proposed as a means of limiting emissions of
green house gases blamed for global warming, he said.
</P>
<P>
While praising some developed countries which "have taken
giant steps in stabilizing their emission to 1990 levels", the
FEPA chief urged the others "who have breached faith to be more
committed to the principle of the convention for the sake of
humanity".
</P>
<P>
In this respect, it would not be fair to require further
commitment from the developing countries, he said, adding that
doing this "is like asking the hungry to feed the overfed."
</P>
</TEXT>
