<HEADLINE> Russia to Participate in Handling Chemical Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
has said that Russia will take part in the handling of chemical
weapons sunk in the Baltic Sea, in the Skagerrak and Kattegat
straits, according to the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has instructed the interdepartmental commission for
chemical disarmament to participate in the preparation and
implementation of an international program to deal with the
aftermath of the burial of chemical weapons sunk in the above
areas.
</P>
<P>
Presidential spokesman Sergei Yastrahemsky told reporters today
that Russia has sufficient cause to draw the conclusion that the
situation in the areas where chemical weapons have been sunk is
deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
Russian experts believe that extensive pollution in the Baltic
Sea and the North Sea may become a reality within the next few
years, the spokesman noted.
</P>
<P>
Nobody (besides Russia) is planning to raise the issue of some
historical responsibility of particular sides for the burial (of
chemical weapons), Yastrahemsky said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the quantity of toxic substances sunk in the
Baltic Sea is comparable with the overall stocks of the United
States and Russia due to be destroyed in line with the Chemical
Weapons Convention.
</P>
<P>
Russia alone has technology allowing a real settlement of this
problem with minimal costs, he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
