<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU FMs Fail to Reach Compromise on Enlargement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) foreign
ministers tonight failed to reach a compromise they had hoped to
find on how to launch the bloc's eastward enlargement drive
without creating new divisions on the continent.
</P>
<P>
Major questions on the issue, which remain to be solved, will
have to wait until the upcoming EU summit which is going to be
held in Luxembourg Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
The EU leaders are expected at the summit to work out an
invitation list for potential EU new members and the appropriate
treatment which should be given to Turkey, whose application for
EU membership has been complicated by human rights concerns.
</P>
<P>
A diplomat, which asked not to be identified, said today that
it was "really difficult" for the EU foreign ministers to reach
agreement on the two major issues -- an invitation list for the
first wave of EU expansion and how to console the applicants left
out.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the EU's executive body, proposed in
July that the EU should start entry talks next year with the six
countries considered most advanced in economic and political
reforms -- Poland, the Czech Republic, Hungary, Slovenia, Estonia
and Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
However, Sweden and Denmark expressed their concern that the
process would create new divisions across Europe by leaving the
other five applicants -- Latvia, Lithuania, Bulgaria, Romania and
Slovakia -- in the EU's waiting room.
</P>
<P>
The Luxembourg summit is expected to decide whether or not to
begin entry talks with the six applicants on the fast track or
with all the 11 applicants.
</P>
<P>
The ministers were discussing a compromise whereby full
negotiations would only start with Cyprus and the five former
Communist countries, but the others' cases would be "screened"
from the start to make them feel involved.
</P>
<P>
Maintaining that Turkey meets none of the political criteria
laid down by the EU as a potential member, Greece was still
opposed to the inclusion of Turkey in the planned European
Conference of EU candidate countries.
</P>
<P>
"If it is tailored to cater for our relations with Turkey, I
believe that these relations should develop on the level of
substance and not on the level of appearances," Greek Foreign
Minister Theodoros Pangalos told reporters.
</P>
<P>
However, the chances of Turkey's candidature for EU membership
being finally acknowledged has increased in recent weeks since
Germany, an initial opponent, moved in favor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
