<HEADLINE> Spokesman: Turkish Military Operation in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The scale of the Turkish
military operation being carried out in northern Iraq has been
exaggerated by the press, a Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a weekly news briefing, Sermet Atacanli said the
Turkish troops are launching a small-scale cross-border action
against the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
"The effective strength of the troops involved in the action
has been exaggerated," Atacanli said.
</P>
<P>
Around 20,000 Turkish government troops poured across the
Turkish-Iraqi border to round up some 1,000 PKK rebels who
gathered there for the past weeks, local press reported.
</P>
<P>
However, Atacanli failed to reveal how many government troops
are involved in the action.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman pointed out that the ongoing operation is part of
Ankara's efforts to wipe out the PKK rebels who pose a serious
threat to Turkey's border security.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's sovereignty and territorial integrity will be fully
respected during the action, he said, adding that the Turkish
troops will withdraw from the region as soon as their objective is
achieved.
</P>
<P>
"As we said many times, Turkey does not envisage a permanent
military presence in northern Iraq," Atacanli stressed.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Foreign Ministry Saturday issued a statement condemning
Turkey's invasion of northern Iraq, demanding an immediate
pull-out of the Turkish troops.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has lost its effective control over northern Iraq
following the 1991 Gulf War in which it was defeated by the
U.S.-led multinational forces.
</P>
<P>
Ankara launches cross-border incursions every now and then with
an aim to wipe out the camps of the PKK, a group fighting against
the government for independence in southeast Turkey since 1984.
</P>
<P>
Ankara's frequent military operations in northern Iraq has
negatively affected its relations with Arab countries, observers
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
