<HEADLINE> Annan Recommends Sending of Technical Survey Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- UN Secretary-General
Kofi Annan recommended prompt dispatch of a technical team to
Sierra Leone to assess what role the United Nations could play to
help in the implementation of the Conakry Agreement.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council, Annan said the coup of
May, 25, 1997 was a serious blow to Sierra Leone and also to the
subregion. Sierra Leone and its people have suffered greatly from
the overthrow of the democratically elected government and
continue to suffer harm from its effects on their security and
living conditions.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general said it is evident the international
community is determined that the coup must be reversed and the
constitutional order restored as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief said the signing of the Conakry Agreement was a
significant step towards resolving the crisis in Sierra Leone.
However, despite some encouraging indications, little concrete
progress has been made so far in the implementation of the
agreement which should be pursued with a sense of urgency.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the military, political and humanitarian aspects of
the agreement requires further clarification and negotiation, as
well as the early formulation of the practical modalities for its
implementation.
</P>
<P>
He said the United Nations should be prepared to take an active
part in such negotiations and to help yo assure the proper
implementation of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
With the purpose, the UN chief recommended sending of a
technical team to the country.
</P>
<P>
In his report, he also requested his special envoy for Sierra
Leone to make arrangements to reopen a small liaison office in
Sierra Leone subject to acceptable security conditions and the
availability of funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
