<HEADLINE> Air Crash Rescue Operation Over in Irkutsk, Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Rescuers stopped their search
and rescue works Monday night at the site of a deadly air crash in
the Siberian city of Irkutsk, an official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The death toll of the crash, by an An-124 military cargo last
Saturday, reached 66, Minister for Emergency Situations Sergei
Shoigu was quoted as saying by the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
The fate of the 28 people unaccounted for on the ground were
still unknown, Shoigu said, noting that "most probably it will be
hardly possible to identify more than two-thirds of them."
</P>
<P>
Alexander Kamenski, head of the regional department for
emergency situations and civil defense, refuted some media reports
that there were more than 23 people on board the plane.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, State military inspector-secretary of the Russian
Security Council Andrei Kokoshin warned against drawing "hasty
conclusions" about the results of the aircrash.
</P>
<P>
One should wait until the official outcome of the
investigation, he said.
</P>
<P>
The An-124 crashed in a residential district of Irkutsk only a
few seconds after its take-off from the airfield.
</P>
<P>
Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin flew to the crash
site on the other day to probe the tragedy. More than 1,600 people
took part in the rescue operation, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
