<HEADLINE> 1st World Squash Doubles Championships Open in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The inaugural World Squash
Doubles Championships opened at the Hong Kong Football Club, Happy
Valley on Tuesday, but the competitions proper are set to begin on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 players from 14 countries and regions are to
compete in the four-day event. Among them are Australia's women's
world number one Sarah Fitzgerald and her fifth-ranked partner
Carol Owens, and, in the men's division, 10th-ranked Chris Walker
and 13th ranked Mark Cairns from Britain and 11th-ranked
Australian Dan Jenson and his partner Craig Rowland, 28th in the
world.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's six-time world singles champion Jahangir Khan has
quit from the championships for a foot injury.
</P>
<P>
A new purpose built doubles courts were ready at the Hong Kong
Football Club and the championships also feature the erection of
the clear view portable squash court in the sports hall, which is
up to international standard.
</P>
<P>
Three events have been set for the championships -- men's and
women's doubles and mixed doubles.
</P>
<P>
The men's and women's doubles events will each have 12 teams,
pooled into Groups A and B with six each for preliminaries. Top
two teams from each group advance into the semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
The mixed doubles event will see single knock-out play among
the 10 teams.
</P>
<P>
The total prize money for the championships is set for 400,000
HK dollars (51,200 U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
