<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> El Nino Causes Light Damages to S. California </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The weekend's powerful
Pacific storm hit Southern California's Orange County the hardest,
but causing only light damages to local residents.
</P>
<P>
The El Nino-related storm, starting to sweep across Southern
California Friday, dumped nearly eight inches of rain in Laguna
Beach, Orange County. Scores of houses and mobile homes were
damaged, but most of them were minor, limiting the direct damages
to about 10 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
A 40-year-old mother of five died after she got down a mountain
to pick up her youngest son. Her body was discovered by rescue
workers in the Angeles National Forest.
</P>
<P>
There were no reports of further injuries or drownings, despite
several unconfirmed reports of people and children being swept
away by churning waters, said emergency officials.
</P>
<P>
The light damages might be attributed to sound preparations for
the storm before the weekend, when teams from the U.S. Army Corps
of Engineers cleared the Los Angeles River flood control channel
and swift-water rescue teams drilled in every county.
</P>
<P>
Red Cross officials also made door-to-door stops beforehand in
Laguna Beach, Huntington Beach and Costa Mesa, asking if people
needed help.
</P>
<P>
During the past two days, 49 residents spent night at a Red
Cross emergency shelter set up at a local school while 525 warm
meals were served to the flood victims.
</P>
<P>
Rain stopped Monday but weather forecasters said a cold front
would follow and bring the chilliest temperature of the year to
Southern California by Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Snow and freezing temperatures were already reported in local
mountains, which made driving hazardous on some California
highways.
</P>
<P>
Emergency teams and residents are preparing for the next storm,
which weather experts said would possibly arrive later this week.
</P>
<P>
For the United States, El Nino will make itself known by the
"intensity, frequency and location" of winter storms expected to
lash the southern tier of states from California to Florida from
mid-December to January, meteorologist said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
