<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Grants Aid to Trans-European Energy Networks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
executive body of the European Union (EU), will grant 18 million
ECUs (about 22 million U.S. dollars) as further financial support
for trans-European energy networks.
</P>
<P>
The aid, intended for 16 feasibility studies to pave the way
for construction of these networks, was the second financial grant
approved by the EU this year in this field, said a press release
issued in Brussels Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This will help co-finance 11 trans-European electricity schemes
with 6.2 million ECUs (some 7.5 million dollars) and five studies on
trans-European gas projects with 11.8 million ECUs (about 14
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
"These trans-European networks play an essential role in future
Union energy policy, not only with regard to completion of the
internal energy market but also for our security of supply and
operational flexibility," Christos Papoutsis, EU energy
commissioner, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The aid will bring the total granted by the EU executive to
studies of this kind up to 50 million ECUs (some 60 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The electricity schemes receiving support will upgrade the
interconnections between Portugal and Spain, between Spain and
France and between Ireland and Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The schemes will also establish new interconnections between the
United Kingdom and Norway, between Sweden and Poland, between
central Europe and the Baltic zone and between central Europe and
eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
The gas network projects will help reinforce the gas pipeline
and underground storage system in Austria, which is a key crossroad
for Europe's gas supplies, and to establish new underground storage
sites for natural gas in Spain and Ireland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
