<HEADLINE> PGA Championship in HK to Decide Omega Order of Merit Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 9 (Xinhua) -- For the second time in three
years, the race for golf's Omega Order of Merit title will be
decided at the 500,000 U.S. dollars Omega PGA Championship
starting at the scenic Clearwater Bay Golf and Country Club
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Although any one of top ten players can still mathematically
win Asia's most prestigious golfing award after last week's Hong
Kong Open, the winner of the moneylist is actually more likely to
come from the top five money-earners.
</P>
<P>
Leading the challenge and strong favorite to win the title of
the four-day event, is the current Omega Order of Merit leader
Mike Cunning from the United States.
</P>
<P>
Following his joint ninth place finish at the Hong Kong Open,
Cunning heads the Order of Merit with 170,619 U.S. dollars in
prize money, 46,813 more than the second-placed Prayad Marksaeng,
31, of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Prayad's chances of catching up with the American rival
suffered a lot as he decided to skip the Hong Kong Open, which
allowed Cunning to steal even more ground over the two-time winner
on the 1997 circuit.
</P>
<P>
Lying in the third place on the Order of Merit with 107,091 US
dollars is India's Jeev Milkha Singh. Qualifying recently for
next year's PGA European Tour, Jeev has a disappointing week at
the Hong Kong Open, where he finished tied for 46th.
</P>
<P>
Back to defend his title this week, and still in with a slim
chance of securing the Order of Merit crown, is Gerry Norquist of
America. Norquist lies fifth on the Order ranking with 105,711
U.S. dollars, a mere three dollars behind compatriot Ted Purdy in
fourth place.
</P>
<P>
Norquist finished tied for 28th place in the Hong Kong Open,
and will looking to repeat his form earlier in the season when he
took the DFS Galleria Guam Open.
</P>
<P>
Outstanding in the 132-strong field from 22 countries and
regions is the 1996 Omega Order of Merit winner Kang Wook-soon
from South Korea. Having had a disappointing season to-date, Kang
showed signs of a return to form by finishing runner-up to New
Zealand's Frank Nobilo at the Hong Kong Open.
</P>
<P>
Among others to note were 1995 Omega OGA champion Yeh
Chang-ting from Chinese Taipei and Zaw Moe from Myanmar, winner of
the Singapore Open in August.
</P>
<P>
The Omega PGA Championship represents the final strokeplay
event of the 1997 Omega Tour, and the final Major of the Asian PGA
season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
