<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Help More Farmers Escape Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- China plans to allocate some
four million US dollars over the next three years to help some
60,000 farmers escape poverty, according to the State Science and
Technology Commission (SSTC).
</P>
<P>
The goal of the project, which involves a large number of poor
farmers living over a wide area, is to introduce advanced
technology to poverty-stricken regions in order to help farmers
develop resources more efficiently and raise the productivity of
local laborers.
</P>
<P>
Officials point to the fact that preparatory work has been
completed, and note that the United Nations Development Program
has donated 1.85 million US dollars to fund the project which
covers 10 counties in six provinces.
</P>
<P>
SSTC Vice-Minister Han Deqian said the project, the first of
its kind in China, will offer mortgage-free loans to
poverty-stricken families.
</P>
<P>
"Participating farmers will have access to free technical
training and long-term technical support," said Han, adding that
the government will help farmers sell their products.
</P>
<P>
China has reduced its rural poverty-stricken population from
250 million in 1978 to the current 58 million. Two decades of
effort has also reduced the poverty rate from 33.3 percent to 6.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
China's poverty-stricken population currently accounts for only
five percent of the worldwide total, compared to 25 percent only
20 years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
