<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elf Again Discovers Giant Oilfield off Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The French oil group
Elf-Aquitaine has discovered a giant offshore oilfield off the
coast of Angola, the daily Le Figaro reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The oilfield, 1,250 meters under water in the Guinea Gulf and
about 200 kilometers northwest of Luanda, is the group's third
biggest discovery in the "bloc 17" exploration zone since May 1996.
</P>
<P>
It is reportedly believed to contain more than 100 million
metric tons of oil, or about 730 million barrels of oil, which is
equivalent to one year's consumption by the French economy.
</P>
<P>
With such a huge reserve, it could probably be the most
fruitful one in the history of oil exploration, said the report.
</P>
<P>
In "bloc 17," Elf is the operator with 35 percent of the
shares, while its partners Esso has 20 percent, British Petroleum
16.67 percent, the Norwegian Statoil 13.33 percent, Norsk-Dydro 10
percent and the Belgian Fina 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The oil group scored its first discovery in May 1996 in "bloc
17" 1,350 meters under water. The oilfield, named "Girassol," was
regarded as an "elephant" with more than 660 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
Elf announced the discovery of a second oilfield, Dalia, in
August 1997 only three kilometers from "Girassol." Although no
official data have been published, it is circulated among oil
circles that it contains 100 million tons of oil, or 700 million
barrels.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, only four oil fields of such a scale have been
discovered by oil companies, and Elf joined in three of them, said
le Figaro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
