<HEADLINE> Angola, Congo to Ensure Border Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Angola and the Congo Republic
(Brazzaville) will beef up security along their common borders,
the Angola News Agency reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the two neighbors decided to set up a
joint technical committee to assess the situation in their border
areas when Angolan Minister of the Interior Andre Pitra Petroff
met his Congolese counterpart Piere Oba in Cabinda on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that not only the separatism groups of Cabinda
Province but also soldiers of the opposition of National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), and troops of
former Zaire President Mobutu Sese Seko and former Congolese
President Pascal Lissouba have gathered along the common border
of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The presentation of troops is threatening to the security and
safety in the border areas, which is worrying the two governments
of Angola and Congo, the report added.
</P>
<P>
After investigations into the border situation by the joint
technical committee, the two ministers of the interior will meet
again to discuss security and defense issues and take measures to
strengthen security along the common border, said the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
