<HEADLINE> Li Ruihuan Visits Vietnam's Largest City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HO CHI MINH CITY, Vietnam, December 9 (Xinhua) -- There is
great potential and broad future for the cooperation between Ho
Chi Minh City and Shanghai, the largest economic centers of
Vietnam and China respectively.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made here Tuesday by Li Ruihuan, a Standing
Committee member of the Political Bureau of the Communist Party of
China (CPC) Central Committee, during his meeting with Truong Tan
Sang, secretary of the Ho Chi Minh City Committee of the Communist
Party of Vietnam (CPV).
</P>
<P>
Li, also chairman of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference National Committee, said the cooperation
between the two cities, both the pioneers in the reform and
opening-up drives of the two countries, will push forward the
cooperation between China and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Ho Chi Minh City and Shanghai became twin-cities in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Li arrived here Tuesday morning from Hanoi, the capital of the
country, to continue his visit to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Sang said that since the city became the sister of China's
cities of Shanghai and Guangzhou, the exchanges between the two
sides have been strengthened.
</P>
<P>
He said that Vietnam, which is making commitment to reform and
opening up, needs to learn experiences of economic development and
reform and opening-up from China.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day in Hanoi, Li paid his respect to the remains of
Ho Chi Minh, present the wreath to the mausoleum of this great
leader of Vietnam, and visited his former residence.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving the capital, Li made his farewells to Le Kha
Phieu, a Standing Committee member of the Political Bureau of CPV
Central Committee, and Le Quang Dao, chairman of the Central
Committee of the Fatherland Front of Vietnam. 
</P>
