<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sees Chance to Build True Partnership in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said here today that the U.S. has today an
opportunity, unprecedent since African states gained their
independence, to build a true partnership in the Great Lakes
region.
</P>
<P>
Albright said that "a successful effort will support peace and
the rule of law, promote good governance and democracy, and
encourage economic development and integration" in the region.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Secretary of State was making a speech entitled "the
United States, Africa and the Great Lakes" before African
diplomats.
</P>
<P>
She said that the United States hopes to work with leaders
across the region in a Great Lakes justice initiative, to develop
judicial systems that are impartial, credible and effective.
</P>
<P>
She announced that the U.S. will provide 30 million US Dollars
to support national initiatives to train court and police
officials, re-build legal machinery and assist programs that
promote reconciliation and healing after conflict.
</P>
<P>
On the situation in the Democratic Republic of Congo, Albright
said that the end of Mobutu's repressive reign has opened a
historic opportunity for the Congolese people to achieve the
democracy, prosperity and peace they have been so long denied.
</P>
<P>
However, she stressed that the Kabila government has a great
distance to travel to meet the goals of constitutional reform,
democratic elections and economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
She revealed that the United States will contribute 10 million
US Dollars to the World Bank Trust Fund and said that through it,
the international community will support reconstruction projects
that reflect Congolese priorities.
</P>
<P>
She pledged that the United States is expanding aid and
is looking at the possibility of debt relief to the Congo.
</P>
<P>
On the aim of her current visit to Africa, Albright said she
came to Africa to open a dialogue with people from all parts of
Africa, whether they are powerful or impoverished, high officials
or refugees.
</P>
<P>
She said the new African leaders "are challenging the United
States and the international community to get over the
paternalism of the past, to stop thinking of its Africa policy as
a none-too-successful rescue service."
</P>
<P>
She said that the U.S. pledges its best efforts
to nurturing a new partnership that will work to the benefit of
Africans and Americans alike.
</P>
<P>
Albright arrived here last night for a visit to Ethiopia,
which is the first leg of her six-nation African tour. She will
leave here tomorrow morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
