<HEADLINE> World's Largest Air Cargo Facility Topped out in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The world's largest and most
state-of-the-art air cargo facility, SuperTerminal 1, was topped
out in Hong Kong today.
</P>
<P>
Some 500 senior executives representing contractors,
international airlines and Hong Kong's freight forwarding
community, gathered at Chek Lap Kok airport today to celebrate the
topping-out of Hong Kong Air Cargo Terminals Ltd. (HACTL)'s new
air cargo complex.
</P>
<P>
The facility, expected to handle 85 percent of cargo throughput
at the new airport, will be capable of handling up to 2.6 million
tons of air cargo each year. This compares with the 1.5 million
ton handling capacity at HACTL's current air cargo complex at Kai
Tak airport.
</P>
<P>
With the opening of the new airport less than six months away,
HACTL Managing Director Anthony Charter confirmed that HACTL would
be in a position to start operations at Chek Lap Kok in April
1998.
</P>
<P>
"After today's milestone, we will be embarking upon the final
stages of an aggressive construction schedule. It is our
intention to launch operations at Chek Lap Kok at 50 percent
capacity in April," he said.
</P>
<P>
SuperTerminal 1, at the cost of 8 billion HK dollars (1 billion
U.S. dollars), comprises a six-storey main terminal building with
a total floor area of 274,000 square meters and a two-storey
Express Center providing a further 46,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
The facility is equipped with the latest operational technology
and automated systems.
</P>
<P>
Also addressing the ceremony was Peter Sutch, chairman of
Cathay Pacific and Swire Pacific which together hold a 40 percent
stake in HACTL.
</P>
<P>
Sutch commended HACTL's achievement at Kai Tak airport,
congratulating the air cargo operator in surpassing the 1.5
million ton mark in November.
</P>
<P>
Other shareholders of the HACTL are Jardine Pacific, Wharf
Holdings, Hutchison Whampoa Group and China National Aviation
Corporation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
