<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Strives to Standardize Accounting Practices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- A recent government document
vows that China will standardize basic accounting practices within
3-5 years.
</P>
<P>
The document also stipulates severe punishment for those found in
violation of the rules.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that the campaign to rectify order within the
accounting sector yielded positive results during 1996, various
problems such as the falsification of statements, budgets, cost
estimates and profits have not as yet been fundamentally resolved,
according to the document, which was approved by the State Council
and jointly issued by the Ministry of Finance, the Auditing
Administration, the Economic and Trade Commission, the
Administration of Taxation, and the Administration for Industry
and Commerce.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, all sectors and departments should conduct random
audits and reexaminations, and violations must be dealt with
in a resolute manner," according to the document.
</P>
<P>
The document urges all units to maintain accurate accounting
records and stresses that state-owned enterprises must adopt
strict procedures for the use of funds for both consumption and
production.
</P>
<P>
"Basic accounting practices should be standardized within the
next 3-5 years," according to the document.
</P>
<P>
The document also stresses that leading officials are
responsible for the legitimacy and accuracy of balance sheets for
their respective units.
</P>
<P>
Officials from units with inappropriate accounting practices
and those who present falsified balance sheets or
infringe upon the rights of accountants will be held legally
accountable, according to the document.
</P>
<P>
It also urges taxation administrations at all levels to
strengthen management over both ordinary and value-added tax
invoices.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
