<HEADLINE> China Hails Four-Party Talks on Korean Peninsula Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The first session of the
four-party talks being held here on the Korean Peninsula issue is
of great significance, said a senior Chinese diplomat on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It marks the formal beginning of the process toward a peace
mechanism for the peninsula, said Chinese Vice Foreign Minister
Tang Jiaxuan in a key-note statement at the two-day talks.
</P>
<P>
The dialogue, among the Democratic People's Republic of Korea
(DPRK), the Republic of Korea, the People's Republic of China and
the United States, is scheduled to last through Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Replacing the existing armistice mechanism with a new peace
mechanism through the talks, Tang said, undoubtedly has a positive
impact on the process toward a lasting peace on the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
"It is our sincere hope that all parties will treasure this
achievement, persist in dialogues and consultations" within the
framework of the talks, said the head of the Chinese delegation.
</P>
<P>
He also called for a peninsular peace accord "on the basis of
gradual improvement of relations and building mutual trust" among
the parties, so as to achieve the goal of the four-party talks.
</P>
<P>
"As a close neighbor of the Korean Peninsula," he said. "China
takes maintaining peace and stability on the peninsula as the
fundamental principle in its handling of Peninsular affairs."
</P>
<P>
"Over years, China has dedicated itself to maintaining peace
and stability there, endorsing the improvement of relations
between the North and South of Korea and supporting their
independent and peaceful reunification," he added.
</P>
<P>
China believes that the ultimate solution of the Korean issue
requires not only the reconciliation and mutual trust between the
DPRK and South Korea, but also the improved DPRK-U.S. relations,
Tang said.
</P>
<P>
"We are convinced that the steady improvement of North-South
relations and DPRK-US relations will create a favorable atmosphere
and pave the way for further easing of tension and early
establishment of the peace mechanism on the peninsula," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
