<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Builds Refuse Transfer Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 9 (Xinhua) -- A refuse transfer station
built inside a man-made cavern was opened here today, capable of
processing 1,000 tons of waste a day.
</P>
<P>
It was the second waste transfer station built on the Hong Kong
Island, and the other one has already been in operation in the
east part of the Island. Their total handling capacity of waste
added up to more than 2,200 tons, sufficient to accommodate all
waste generated on the Island.
</P>
<P>
The new station was constructed at a cost of 640 million HK
dollars (82 million US dollars), and its annual operation cost is
estimated to reach 56 million HK dollars (7 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
An official of environmental protection said today that noise
and odor nuisance could be greatly reduced since the station was
built inside a man-made cavern and installed with waste water
treatment facility and odor removal equipment.
</P>
<P>
All waste received would be compacted into specially designed
sealed containers and transferred by vessels to a landfill site in
the New Territory for final disposal, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
