<HEADLINE> Kinkel Urges Bosnian Parties to Implement Dayton Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 9 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel Tuesday urged the Bosnian parties to carry on the
implementation of the Dayton peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel made this call at a two-day international conference on
Bosnia peace which opened here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Those who want reconciliation will receive our help. Those who
do not implement Dayton accord, who seek to obstruct the recovery
effort, will bear the consequences," he said at the conference
which is held annually to review the implementation of the accord.
</P>
<P>
Despite progress in disarmament, elections, return of refugees
and economic reconstruction over the past few years, there was
still a lack of will among the Bosnian parties to take the
necessary decisions in building the common institutions as the
basis for further development, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the institutions included a single passport and
nationality law, a common currency, uniform car registration
plates and a law on the functions of the Bosnian Council of
Ministers.
</P>
<P>
He also called it "unacceptable" that most of the indicted war
criminals including Radovan Karadzic were still free in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
He said that the international community would not back off
until all of the accused had been brought to account.
</P>
<P>
The conference, attended by representatives from 51 countries
and 21 interanational organizations, will also discuss the
deficiencies in Bosnian judicial and law enforcement system and
will boost measures to fight corruption in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
