<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: More Countries Get Wired to the Net </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The year 1997 has seen more
countries getting wired and more people jumping online as computer
networking gains greater momentum throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Such terms as internet, intranet and extranet are acquiring
more and more currency among political leaders, business
executives and the man in the street.
</P>
<P>
While the developed nations try to sharpen their competitive
edge in the networking business, the developing ones, becoming
more aware of the huge "Net" potential, are trying desperately to
catch up.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays you can do virtually anything in the virtual world of
cyberspace. Networking has breathed new life into almost all
facets of life, from industry, agriculture, telecommunications,
transportation to education and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the value of electronic commerce conducted over the
Net totaled nearly 3 billion U.S. dollars. The value is expected
to increase annually by 100 percent in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
"The Internet is going to change everything, and at a pace we
have never seen before," said John Chambers, CEO of the
California-based Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
In Canada and the United States where the net was born,
Internet use doubled over the 18 months ending in March, according
to a survey by CommerceNet/Nielsen Media Research,
</P>
<P>
Almost one out of four -- 23 percent of people over the age of
16 -- in the two countries now use the Internet as opposed to only
10 percent in the fall of 1995, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
The European Union, somewhat lagging behind in recent years,
has proposed laws to promote the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the EU's executive arm, plans to
increase investment in research and development, develop computer
networks and encourage start-up ventures to help make the EU more
competitive.
</P>
<P>
In Asia, the region that witnessed the fastest economic growth,
networking is also booming.
</P>
<P>
At the end of October, China had more than 100 Internet service
providers and 600,000 online users, said Lu Xinquan of the
Information Task Force under the country's State Council.
</P>
<P>
China plans to inject an annual 100 billion yuan (about 12
billion dollars) in 1996-2000 to build fiber-optic cables and
satellite communications facilities.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this century, all residents of Singapore will be
connected by a high-speed, broad-band network.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's construction of a Multimedia Super Corridor in and
around the capital of Kuala Lumpur is gaining steam. Cyberjava
City, a high-tech manufacturing area where homes and buildings
will be equipped from the start to send, receive and process
electronic information, held a ground-breaking ceremony recently.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia, still struggling to rebuild itself from the rubble of
war and unrest, established a full-time Internet connection in May.
</P>
<P>
Africa is also stepping up Internet development. Five West
African nations passed a declaration in April calling for
expedited establishment of the Net in the region.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless a formidable disparity still remains between the
developed and the developing countries in computer networking.
</P>
<P>
According to a report released by the International
Telecommunications Union in September, two-thirds of the world's
Internet users are in the United States and Canada, 21.9 percent
on the European continent, 6.3 percent in Asia and 3.7 percent in
Oceania. Internet users in Latin America and Africa account for
only 1 percent and 0.6 percent of the total respectively.
</P>
<P>
Although the yawning gap cannot be bridged easily or soon, the
developing countries are not without opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries can embark from a better established
starting point and thereby avoid the pitfalls encountered by their
developed counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Networking needs many specialized talents. Developing nations
such as China and India, with a large number of specialists in
computer softwares and related fields pooled over the years, are
capable of competing with the developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Networking technology has advanced the development of network
computers, the production of which is relatively simpler. The
developing countries are able to capitalize on this opportunity to
develop and consolidate their fledgling computer industry and
related sectors.
</P>
<P>
More importantly, the developing countries recognize the
importance of information technology to economic growth and have
put net development on the top of their agenda.
</P>
<P>
As Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad put
it: "Eventually the entire world will have to come to use this new
technology, which seems to have no respect for borders."
</P>
<P>
And such a world online will surely be a smaller, and better,
place to live. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNSCOM Chief in Paris to Discuss Arms Inspection in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The chairman of the United
Nations Special Commission in charge of disarmament in Iraq
(UNSCOM), Richard Butler, held talks with French Defense Minister
Alain Richard Tuesday in Paris on the role of UNSCOM in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has called for the increase of the number of French experts
in the UNSCOM, which has been so far dominated by English-speaking
and Nordic countries.
</P>
<P>
No official declaration was made after the meeting, but Agence
France-Presse (AFP) said that the talks should be focused on the
methods of functioning of the UNSCOM and the question of access by
UNSCOM inspectors to the presidential sites.
</P>
<P>
Butler will hold talks later Tuesday with French Foreign
Minister Hubert Vedrine and other French Foreign Ministry
officials, said Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM chief will fly to Baghdad for the first time in a
few days since the crisis between Iraq and UNSCOM erupted in late
October, in a bid to persuade Iraqi government to let UNSCOM
experts enter presidential sites, which are so far banned from
inspections.
</P>
<P>
France has called on Iraq to show restraint and moderation, and
rejected Iraqi insistence on excluding UNSCOM members from
presidential sites.
</P>
<P>
The French government hoped that a
pragmatic solution can be found for the stand-off between Baghdad
and the international community, and wished the United Nations to
offer Iraq a perspective for the lifting of the economic sanctions
imposed against Baghdad since its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
