<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guizhou to Draft Law to Protect Rare Cranes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Guizhou
Province will work out detailed plans to deal with the environmental
deterioration of its most famous wetland nature reserve,
according to a senior local official.
</P>
<P>
The Provincial People's Congress will draft Guizhou's first
regulation to ban illegal zinc smelteries around the Caohai Nature
Reserve, according to Wang Shusen, vice-chairman of the Standing
Committee of the Provincial People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
Some 500 black-necked cranes normally migrate from the
Qinghai-Tibet Plateau to Caohai's grassy marshes which cover
25 sq. km. in poverty-stricken Weining County, according to a
nature reserve official.
</P>
<P>
Experts note that the nature reserve faces the possibility of
severe pollution if environmental protection departments fail to
take decisive action.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that any failure to act will deprive rare cranes
and other migratory waders of their winter habitat in Caohai.
</P>
<P>
"Approximately 33 percent of Weining's wastewater pours into
Caohai without any form of treatment," said an official
with the Guizhou Environmental Protection Bureau (GEPB).
</P>
<P>
He noted that the existing pollution currently threatens the
life of migratory cranes.
</P>
<P>
Wang estimated that sewage disposal plants will cost the
province some two million yuan (240,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Some 20,000 farmers living in close proximity to the nature
reserve earn their livelihoods from farming. The large population
and limited natural resources in the Caohai area present a
challenge to both conservation and development, according to the
GEPB official.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey carried out by the GEPB revealed that zinc
smelteries near the wetland are an even greater threat to the
nature reserve.
</P>
<P>
Smoke, dust and sulphur dioxide emissions from the 211 furnaces
have harmed both birds and local residents. Waste gases and other
heavy metal elements from the smelteries will cause even greater
environmental damage in the future, according to the official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
