<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Peace Conference Opens in Bonn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 9 (Xinhua) -- An international conference opened
here Tuesday to review the implementation of the Dayton accord for
bringing peace back to Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The annual event, the third of its kind, is aimed at increasing
international pressure on the Bosnian leadership for better
compliance with the November 1995 accord.
</P>
<P>
Its organizers also intend to bring new impetus to a
"self-sustainable" political and economic development in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting are delegates from 51 countries and 21
international organizations, including Bosnian presidency members,
Alija Izetbegovic, Kresimir Zubak and Momcilo Krajisnik, as well
as the president of the Srpska Republic, Biljana Plavsic.
</P>
<P>
To see that commitments made at Dayton, the United States, were
not being honored, said German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel, is
"insufferable" for the international community.
</P>
<P>
The world community has been providing major funding, personnel
and military resources to Bosnia, Kinkel, the host of the two-day
meeting, noted prior to its opening.
</P>
<P>
"Whoever cooperates with the peace process will be rewarded,
whoever sows hatred and discord will be punished financially," he
warned.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel and his French counterpart Hubert Vedrine traveled to
Sarajevo last Thursday to push for long-overdue decisions by the
Bosnian leadership on a series of issues before the Bonn meeting.
</P>
<P>
These included a single passport and citizenship law, a
common currency, national auto-registration numbers and the
composition of the Bosnian national council of ministers.
</P>
<P>
If the Bosnians wanted continued international aid, said
Kinkel, they should not show up in Bonn empty-handed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
