<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Voters Cool on Poll For Constitutional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- More than half of Australia's
voters have rejected a poll on selecting delegates to next year's
constitutional convention which will decide whether Australia
would become a republic.
</P>
<P>
Latest turnout figures show that only 44.2 percent, or 5.3
million of Australia's almost 12 million registered voters replied
to the voluntary postal poll, a trial one for selecting half of
the delegates to February's constitutional convention.
</P>
<P>
The figures show a late rush of votes, with the ACT (Australian
Capital Territory) and Victoria state having the highest
participation rate of 49.14 percent and 48.95 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
But even with a late surge in ballots, national turnout was
expected to remain well below 50 per cent.
</P>
<P>
The returns signal public apathy for the convention, which will
see 76 elected and 76 appointed delegates attempt to thrash out a
consensus on an alternative constitutional system for Australia.
</P>
<P>
Supporters of a republic were today confident of a positive
result. They said more people voted from the electorates of the
Labor Party, most members in which favor a republic, while turnout
in regional and National Party electorates was low. The National
Party leaders are for the current constitutional monarchy system.
</P>
<P>
But all sides were disappointed by the low response.
</P>
<P>
Opposition spokesman Nick Bolkus said up to 1.5 million, mainly
younger Australians who had changed address since the last
election, did not receive a ballot paper.
</P>
<P>
"The major problem is that the result opens up the possibility
that whoever loses could then play the spoiler, by saying any
result is not truly representative," Bolkus said.
</P>
<P>
Special Minister of State Nick Minchin, who is responsible for
the republic issue, said in a statement that "the level of voter
turnout reflects the level of interest in the question of a
republic, and the intensity of the campaigns by the various groups
and individuals contesting the election."
</P>
<P>
"It must also be remembered that this election was to chose
half of the delegates to attend the convention. It was not to
decide the issue of whether or not Australia should become a
republic, which can only be determined by a compulsory attendance
vote in a referendum."
</P>
<P>
First results from the poll are due late tomorrow.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
