<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Benefit from Reading Rooms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Gao En, a 73-year-old farmer
in Nong'an County of northeast China's Jilin Province, started
collecting various kinds of newspapers in 1960, enabling him to
set up a household reading room.
</P>
<P>
Gao's reading room, with a floor space of more than 40 square
meters, now has more than 2,000 books in 10 varieties,
127 various publications and 250 books of newspaper clippings. The
reading room has been used by 10,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Gao's reading room is one of the 2,000 medium-sized reading
rooms in the province.
</P>
<P>
Tiexi Village in Nong'an County established a reading
association in 1994, where local farmers can learn about what
happened in the country, the world and, more importantly, in
farming.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has launched the "Book Store Project" in
rural areas to improve farmers' cultural quality so as to raise
agricultural productivity.
</P>
<P>
Lin Guocai is one of the beneficiaries of the
project. Vegetable growing technology has ensured his income will
reach 40,000 yuan (about 4,787 US. dollars) this year, though his
grain output will drop by 40 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
