<HEADLINE> Newly-elected HK NPC Deputies Vow to Serve Country (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The 36 newly elected deputies
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) to China's
Ninth National People's Congress (NPC) have voiced their readiness
to participate in the management of state affairs.
</P>
<P>
The 36 were elected by the Election Conference through secrete
balloting Monday. This was the first time for Hong Kong to elect
NPC deputies as an independent constituency.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the election results were announced in Hong Kong,
newly elected NPC deputies were busy granting interviews to
newsmen outside the election hall or in their offices.
</P>
<P>
Of the 36 NPC deputies, four are females including Rita Fan Hsu
Lai-tai, president of the Provisional Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
She said in an exclusive interview with Xinhua that she very
much cherished the chance to be a Hong Kong NPC deputy.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the importance of the election, the first of its kind
in Hong Kong's history, she said involvement in the election is
an embodiment of performing a Chinese citizen's obligation
entrusted by the HKSAR Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
She said, "I am a Chinese. The best I hope for is to make China
strong. To this end, I will work hard and serve as a 'bridge'
between Hong Kong and the inland areas."
</P>
<P>
"The paramount task for me to be a good NPC deputy is to
acquaint myself with the operations of the NPC and the latest
progress of the inland areas," she added.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Tsang Hin Chi, chairman of the Goldlion Holdings Limited,
said that he was pleased to see that the Election Conference
members and the nominees encouraged one another, creating a very
good atmosphere for the election.
</P>
<P>
As a newly elected HK deputy to the NPC, he said he will fully
abide by the Constitution of the People's Republic of China and
the HKSAR Basic Law, and will not interfere in the affairs which
the SAR administers on its own.
</P>
<P>
"I will try my best to continue to play the role of a bridge in
boosting economic links between China's inland areas and Hong
Kong and promote their mutual understanding and respect under the
two different systems," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
