<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Efficiency Initiative for HK's Export Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 9 (Xinhua) -- A Supply Chain Management
(SCM) initiative was introduced here today to increase the
competitiveness and efficiency of Hong Kong's export companies.
</P>
<P>
A road map on SCM in global trade was launched by the Hong Kong
Article Numbering Association (HKANA), following a study
supervised by the Export SCM Steering Committee comprising leading
Hong Kong export companies.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by Kurt Salmon Associates Management
Consultants (KSA) for the HKANA, highlighted the fact that for
Hong Kong's export industry to remain successful, exporters must
do business differently from today's traditional ways.
</P>
<P>
The companies need to adopt SCM to improve efficiency, with the
need for change driven by the retail trends in major Western
consumer product markets.
</P>
<P>
In the United States, Germany and Britain, traditional
pre-season orders are increasingly replaced by speed sourcing
(last-minute ordering) and more replenishment orders
(within-season ordering).
</P>
<P>
"SCM is a way of conducting business that requires trading
partners to collaborate and integrate many aspects of their
operations, using global standard practices and technologies, in
order to effectively manage the supply and demand of goods and
services," said Anna Lin, chief executive of the HKANA, a member
of an international organization promoting SCM.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong companies need to invest in electronic commerce and
communications system in order to decrease cycle time and
inventory overheads, she said.
</P>
<P>
The study suggested that timely implementation of SCM in Hong
Kong could lead to annual savings of 9.2 billion HK dollars (1.2
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
A series of workshops and seminars will be held by HKANA next
year to improve the local awareness of the importance of
SCM. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
