<HEADLINE> ILO Calls For Effective Workers' Benefit Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bangkok, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Michel Hansenne,
director-general of the International Labor Organization (ILO)
today warned of the potentially grave social consequences of the
financial turmoil in Asia and called for effective unemployment
benefit systems for workers.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of a three-day ILO Asian regional
meeting here, Hansenne also called on representatives of ILO Asian
and Pacific members to facilitate worker redeployment and increase
opportunities for education and skills acquisition.
</P>
<P>
He said if the sudden onset of the current economic crisis is
not quelled speedily, it is likely to see strong negative impact
on the real economy and hence on employment and the welfare of
workers.
</P>
<P>
The social consequences of a sharp increase in unemployment
could be catastrophic because of the weakness of the existing
system of social protection in most parts of Asia, Hansenne said.
</P>
<P>
He added that there is typically no system of unemployment
benefits or mechanism for facilitating re-training and
redeployment. Consequently, jobless workers will have to fend for
themselves and rely on family and other traditional social support
systems.
</P>
<P>
The ILO meeting is being held to consider a range of issues of
concern to the ILO -- employment, poverty, human resources
development, industrial relations, and protection of workers,
women and child laborers -- in the broad perspective of
globalization of economies and liberalization of trade.
</P>
<P>
Globalization will not be politically viable if it leads to a
deterioration in social justice, the ILO director-general said,
adding that rising inequality, deteriorating labor welfare, and
the absence of adequate social protection could "breed discontent
and provoke a strong backlash against globalization."
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, participants from 43 ILO members of the region
representing governments, employers and workers will forge new
strategies for ILO future activities in the region on a wide range
of social issues.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
