<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Industry Up 11.6 Percent in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- China's industrial sector
registered a steady growth last month, with the added value of all
the enterprises above township-level amounting to 188.4 billion
yuan, up 11.6 percent over the same period in 1996, said a monthly
report released by State Statistical Bureau (SSB) today.
</P>
<P>
During the January-November period, the growth of state-owned
and state-run enterprises increased by a small margin, while the
collectively-owned enterprises and other economic sectors keeping
the same momentum as in the previous months.
</P>
<P>
According to the SSB report, the growth rate of state-owned
sector hit 6.4 percent in November on an annual basis, which was
1.3 percentage points higher than that of last October. The
collectively-owned sector generated a year-on-year increase of
12.7 percent, which was almost the same as that of October.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, light industry realized an added value of 86.7
billion yuan, up 12.2 percent over the same period in 1996. The
heavy industry generated 101.7 billion yuan in added value, up
11.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The production of energy, some raw materials and half of
investment products declined in November. The energy output
amounted to 110 million tons of standard coal, down 0.3 percent
over the same month of last year.
</P>
<P>
In November, the output of coal and crude oil went down by 0.3
percent and 0.1 percent, respectively, on an annual basis, said
the SSB report.
</P>
<P>
Stagnation was also found in the production of nearly a half of
the 30 major machinery and electric products. In November, the
output of internal combustion engines, metal-cutting machine
tools, locomotives, railway passenger coaches and tractors went
down by 3.6 percent to 50.8 percent on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
However, the production of automobiles, program-controlled
switching machines, micro-electronics computers and
super-integrated circuits increased by 8.9 percent to 110 percent.
</P>
<P>
The output of electric fans, household air-conditioners,
refrigerator, bicycles, garment, silk and knitting wool decreased
by 5.4 percent to 37.6 percent. In the mean time, the production
of sugar, beer, chemical fiber, color televisions, video recorders
and acoustic equipment went up by 10.5 percent to 110 percent.
</P>
<P>
The industrial efficiency index of China's 370,000 industrial
enterprises in the first ten months hit 88.95, up 3.43 percentage
points over the same period in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: A Briton Who Writes About HK Success Story (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 9 (Xinhua) -- From a journalist who wrote
about the long-isolated China in the wake of Mao Zedong's death,
to a consultant who co-authored the influential book "The Hong
Kong Advantage" just before Hong Kong's historic handover, Briton
David Dodwell found that Asia has become an increasingly deep
brand on his careers in the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
He joined the Financial Times in September 1976, days before
Chinese leader Mao Zedong died. The paper needed articles on
everything about China, but at that time almost nobody knew about
China since it had been isolated from the rest of the world for so
 long.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1970s, Dodwell happened to teach Chinese diplomats
 in London English, and it was this summer job in college years
that enabled him to have practical contact with the Chinese
people. That was how he started to write about China, and later
about Asia and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Having been in Asia on and off for 20 years, Dodwell
highlighted his insights into the issue of Hong Kong in a book
titled "The Hong Kong Advantage". The book, when published in May
1997, drew the limelight of the international media community that
clustered in Hong Kong for the handover coverage.
</P>
<P>
Its convincible study dispersed doomsday myth that "Hong Kong
is over", highlighted Hong Kong's intrinsic strengths of
adaptation, resilience, and counter-intuitive combinations, and
underpinned challenges faced with the economy.
</P>
<P>
Michael Enright and Edith Scott, a couple from Harvard Business
 School, and Dodwell started the research project on which the
book is based in the autumn of 1995, and completed it a year
later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Provincial Job Network Gives Laid-Off Workers New Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Wang Shanshan, a laid-off
plastics company worker here, has a new, well-paying job as a taxi
driver.
</P>
<P>
Wang had been jobless for two years until she participated in a
special training class sponsored by the Municipal Department of
Labor in Taiyuan, capital of north China's Shanxi Province. She
then bought a taxi and began to earn an eye-catching monthly
salary for ordinary Chinese workers: 5,000 yuan (600 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Wang is only one of the beneficiaries of the city's
re-employment network involving 19 enterprises, 50 training bases
and 10,000 laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
The network includes government-sponsored training classes, and
technical and vocational schools.
</P>
<P>
Established in October, the re-employment network offers
professional training and recommends job opportunities to laid-off
workers. The network also organizes the export of labor services.
</P>
<P>
The Municipal Department of Labor has also promulgated several
other preferential policies to encourage laid-off workers to
engage themselves in such jobs as cleaning apartments and looking
after the elderly and patients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: A Briton Who Writes About HK Success Story (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dodwell said that an important objective of the study was to
provide a group of private business people here with a better and
sound understanding of what are the true strengths and what are
the real problems in the economy, so that they can incorporate
them into their strategies going forward.
</P>
<P>
"Now the book not only provides practical insight for the
private sector, but also practical help for the government
decision makers," he said.
</P>
<P>
Having concluded on the basis of their study that Hong Kong is
perhaps the best place in the world to see the future of the
global economy, Enright and Scott have done what Dodwell did
several years ago -- relocate to Hong Kong. Enright now is a
visiting professor at the University of Hong Kong's School of
Business Administration.
</P>
<P>
On the impact of the recent Asia financial turmoil, Dodwell
said: "I feel it is a valuable test of the strength of Hong
Kong. Hong Kong has very effectively, efficiently mediated the
challenges that swept over it through October."
</P>
<P>
"It illustrated just how flexible this economy is. It takes
shocks very directly, deals with the shocks, absorbs the shocks
and repositions to where it's on, much more quickly than the other
economies do," he went on.
</P>
<P>
One important reason, he argued, is because there are very few
linkages between the government decision making and the business
decision making so that the government can take swift and firm
actions. "In other Asian economies, those linkages are the heart
of the problem," he added.
</P>
<P>
As the book points out, Hong Kong's core strength lies in its
immense flexibility, a wide spread of economic activities, and a
wide spectrum of markets. "Hong Kong is luckily placed to have
good strong business links with the Chinese mainland to give it an
extra area of business activities to keep the economy robust," he
reiterated a unique advantage mentioned in the book.
</P>
<P>
"Of course, Hong Kong's economy has been hurt and will be hurt
for some time because of what has happened in the region, "said
Dodwell, adding that its high flexibility to quickly respond to
changes would again surface to help Hong Kong recover.
</P>
<P>
His strong belief in robustness and resilience of Hong Kong's
economy was built upon his solid experience in the city. As the
first residential correspondent of the Financial Times in Hong
Kong, he worked here for five years between 1984 and 1988.
</P>
<P>
Then back to London, he stayed there for four years, but
finally decided to come back to Hong Kong in 1993, wrapping up his
17-year role as a journalist and starting his second career as a
consultant on trade policy and macroeconomic affairs.
</P>
<P>
"I was impatient about the lack of flexibility and vitality in
the European economy," which he described as a depressed scenario
of protectionism.
</P>
<P>
"The economy here in Asia is buoyant and flexible," he
said. "And I think Hong Kong is a much more interesting option."
</P>
<P>
Another strong pushing factor for his return was that he would
rather be a participant than a spectator. "One of the most
exciting things about returning to Hong Kong is that the work I
was doing was going to have direct policy consequences." He was
delighted to see his work had an influence in decision making
circles in Hong Kong and throughout Asia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ILO Urged to Help Improve Workers' Basic Conditions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Minister of Labor
Li Qiyan said here today that the International Labor Organization
(ILO) should help developing and transitional economies to
overcome their practical difficulties and improve their workers'
basic living and working conditions.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the three-day 12th ILO Asian regional meeting,
which opened here today, Li said, "We always maintain that in
efforts to safeguard and promote the basic rights of workers and
to implement international labor standards, countries should
proceed from their own economic development levels and
socio-cultural realities and work for gradual implementation
through developing the economy and improving legislation."
</P>
<P>
He added, "overlooking the distinctive conditions in countries
and disrespect for the independent choice of each member state and
attempting to force the implementation of international labor
standards through applying pressure with a protectionist mind will
only intensify division and create confrontation, rather than
achieving the desired result."
</P>
<P>
He said some proposals, such as the so-called "social clause",
"social labeling" and an expansion of the supervision mechanism,
rather than helping with the economic development of developing
nations, will only interfere with the employment strategies in
these countries and will not serve the goal of protecting the
basic rights of the workers.
</P>
<P>
Concerning the region, Li said that most Asian nations, because
of their large population and relatively weak economic
fundamentals, are still faced with serious problems such as
poverty, unemployment and semi-employment.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, the promotion of employment and the
elimination of poverty have always been a priority of this region,
and the same should be the focus of ILO in its activities in the
region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Army Ordered to Be Prepared for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Head of State General
Sani Abacha has ordered the national army to be prepared for the
challenges posed by some sections of the international community
with "unjustifiable attempt" to isolate the country.
</P>
<P>
At the opening of this year's Chief of Army Staff annual
training conference on Monday in Enugu, southeastern Nigeria,
Abacha urged the armed forces not to continue to depend on other
countries for vital supplies and training facilities.
</P>
<P>
Instead, the armed forces should "embrace with greater
seriousness the principle of effective management and proper
maintenance of existing facilities," Abacha told the service
chiefs, commanders and administrators at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
He promised that the federal government would continue to
do its best to maintain an army that could efficiently carry out
its constitutional roles.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian military has been facing various sanctions from
west European countries, the United States and Canada following
allegations of human rights abuse which climaxed with the
execution in November 1995 of minority rights activist Ken
Saro-Wiwa and eight of his kinsmen.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions have cut off fresh supplies of military
equipment and spare parts.
</P>
<P>
Although the country is able to produce or even export to
neighboring countries some simple conventional weapons, the
sanctions have added difficulties to the renewal and maintenance
of sophisticated military equipment.
</P>
<P>
While praising the army's efforts to repair air defense weapons
and other military equipment, Abacha also urged the army to
resist attempts by detractors of the government to derail the
political transition program.
</P>
<P>
"Your unalloyed loyalty and dedication to duty are vital to
the successful attainment of our national objectives," said
Abacha. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0130 </DOCNO>
