<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Market Prospects for China's Coal Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Today's edition of the
"Economic Information Daily" reported that China's demand for coal
resources will reach 1.48 billion tons by the year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Projections call for the domestic coal consumption volume to
reach 1.43 billion tons and exports will rise to 50 million tons,
according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
The power generation, heating, metallurgy, chemical, building
materials, transportation, postal services and light industry
sectors will account for the vast majority of coal consumption.
</P>
<P>
China's coal industry has developed steadily since the
beginning of the Ninth Five-Year-Plan Period (1996-2000), with
supply exceeding demand.
</P>
<P>
Projections call for the country to produce 1.42 billion tons
of coal in 1997, thereby surpassing the annual target for the coal
industry.
</P>
<P>
Most of the country's coal is produced in Shanxi Province, the
Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region in North China, and Shaanxi
Province in northwest China.
</P>
<P>
Some 37 billion yuan was earmarked for capital construction in
the coal mining industry between 1996-1997, with the added annual
production capacity slated to reach 63 million tons, according to
the paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
