<HEADLINE> Ten Billion Bonds Launched in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- East African Development Bank
(EADB) has launched here a 10 billion Uganda Shillings (some 10
million U.S. Dollars) floating rate bonds for primary listing,
The Monitor reported today.
</P>
<P>
The bonds will be tradable at the Uganda Securities Exchange
(USE) from January 5 when the exchange market kicks off.
</P>
<P>
The listing of the bonds remains open until December 12 when
checks should get signed up and money put at table.
</P>
<P>
F.R. Tibeita, the Director General of EADB, said the operation
is aimed at collecting money to support long term projects.
</P>
<P>
EADB has succeeded in Kenya, but in Uganda, it needs to go a
long way to spur development.
</P>
<P>
The EADB bonds shall trade on the 182 treasury bill rate plus
discount marging of two percent.
</P>
<P>
EADB authorities said that the interest of the bonds shall be
repaid in eight instalments over four years. Every 12.50 percent
of the bonds will be repaid for every six months.
</P>
<P>
The bonds are underwritten by Nile Bank as the leading
institution with 70 percent of the stake worth of 6.1 billion,
and the Merchant Bank and the National Bank of Kenya.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
