<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Draft Bill on Human Rights Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is now
finalizing the draft of a bill to set up National Human Rights
Commission (NHRC) which is likely to be placed before the
Parliament session next month, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The present government has given special consideration to the
long standing demand by civil society and human rights
organizations for setting up the NHRC, the Bangladesh Observer
stated.
</P>
<P>
According to the draft bill, the president will constitute the
NHRC in consultation with the prime minister, parliament speaker
and the opposition leader in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The chairperson of the commission will be appointed from among
the retired judges of the Appellate Division of the Supreme Court,
and four members of the commission will be selected from among
persons having knowledge or practical experience in matters
relating to human rights. At least one female member will be
included in the commission.
</P>
<P>
The five-member commission will be formed for a term of five
years, the draft bill says.
</P>
<P>
The NHRC will have the power to institute inquiry on a petition
or complaint by a victim due to violation of human rights or
negligence by a public servant.
</P>
<P>
The commission can intervene in any proceeding involving any
allegation of violation of human rights pending before a court
with the approval of the concerned court, according to the draft
bill.
</P>
<P>
The draft bill will encourage the efforts of the
Non-Governmental Organizations and other private institutions
working in the fields of human rights.
</P>
<P>
The commission will recommend appropriate measures to stop the
acts of terrorism that inhibit the enjoyment of human rights.
</P>
<P>
The NHRC will be deemed to be a civil court with judicial
proceedings, and all members of the commission will function
without political or official interference, and the annual or
special reports of the commission will be placed before the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The commission will be financed through a Trust Fund to be
created by the government with the approval of Parliament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
