<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Farmers Lose 90% Yearly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian farmers lose about 90
percent of their agricultural yields every year to poor seeds and
other artificial hazards, the Daily Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The farmers are compelled to produce below 10 percent capacity
yield per land unit due to the traditional planting of low yield
seeds and lack of government support, according to Murtala Nyako,
President of the Practicing Farmers Association of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in the country, he said, had been constrained in
competing with others at international level because of their low
production capacity.
</P>
<P>
The quality of their products was equally not encouraging, he
said at a news conference on enhanced agricultural activities
held recently in Kano, North Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The president asserted that farmers in Nigeria were still
producing at subsistence level, pointing out that even the
large-scale farming class had crumbled because their production
capacity could not pay the production cost.
</P>
<P>
To address the low yield production problem, Nyako advised
that the government should as a matter of urgency support the
farmers by providing them with loans, improved hybrid seeds and
education on extension service delivery.
</P>
<P>
The government should also subsidize input and coordinate
export opportunities for farmers, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
