<HEADLINE> Israeli Sanitation Workers Continue Striking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Despite the end of the
crippling five-day nationwide strike Monday, Israeli sanitation
workers in Tel Aviv decided to continue striking today, Israel
Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The workers, objecting to the city's hiring private
contractors to collect garbage, made the decision after their
representatives failed to reach an agreement with Tel Aviv
Municipal government Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Trade Union Chairman Amir Peretz, who signed an
agreement with the Treasury ending the general strike Monday,
met Tel Aviv Mayor Ronni Milo later in the day in an attempt to
broker a compromise between the municipality and the striking
workers.
</P>
<P>
Although Peretz proposed that as a compromise the city employ
private contractors to clean up just four city quarters, using
no more than eight trucks, the striking workers insisted on
further negotiations with the municipality.
</P>
<P>
In certain parts of Tel Aviv, citizens were spotted walking
around in gas masks, white sanitary masks, or simply covering
their noses and mouths with their shirts or handkerchiefs.
</P>
<P>
In other places, business owners closed down their shops
because the heaps of garbage filling the sidewalks and pilling
over into the streets prevented access to their shops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
