<HEADLINE> Share Prices Fall on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Share prices declined on the
Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials Index
fell (STII) back by 19.11 points to close at 1,734.22 points
today.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that share prices closed lower on profit-taking
activities with sentiment affected by a correction in the
Malaysian market following a surge in the past couple of days.
Signs of a sharply weaker demand in cars also helped push the STII
down, they added.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume shrank to 228.2 million units, valued
at 463.23 million Singapore dollars (285.94 million U.S. dollars).
Declines overwhelmed advances by 256 to 95, while 259 other
counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Technologies (ST) Engineering again was the most
actively traded stock as it registered a turnover of 44.13 million
units. It was followed by Asia Food and Property (AFP) which had
14.95 million shares traded. RHB Capital Warrant 99 was next with
8.9 million units changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Local computer sound card maker Creative 50 led the gainers of
the day as it rose by 1.2 dollars to end at 36 Singapore dollars.
The DBS (Development Bank of Singapore) Foreign and soft drinks
and food maker F&AMP;N increased by 40 cents each to close at 16.9 and
9.65 Singapore dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, the Singapore Press Holdings (SPH) Foreign was
the biggest loser as it declined by 70 cents to finish at 22.4
Singapore dollars. Malaya Banking fell by 40 cents to close at
five dollars, while Jurong Shipyard was 35 cents lower to end at
9.15 Singapore dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
