<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Unemployment Rises by 27% in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Unemployment in Nigeria
increased by 27 percent this year from the 9.6 percent recorded
last year, according to the latest statistics released by the
country's Organized Private Sector (OPS).
</P>
<P>
The figures were contained in the OPS 1998 pre-budget
memorandum submitted to the federal government recently, This
Day, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The OPS consists of members of the Manufacturers Association
of Nigeria (MAN), firms which belong to the Nigerian Association
of Chambers of Commerce, Industry, Mines and Agriculture
(NACCIMA) and Members of the Nigerian Employers Consultative
Association (NECA).
</P>
<P>
The bodies, which made a joint pre-budget memorandum for the
first time this year, attributed the contraction of employment
this year to the large-scale rationalization of human and natural
resources in both the public and private sectors.
</P>
<P>
Of the 17 sectors which the OPS sampled in its 1997 employment
survey, only two, agriculture and allied services and training,
education/consultancy sectors recorded increase in their average
workforce.
</P>
<P>
The other fifteen sectors recorded employment drops of between
8.4 and 91.7 percent in the year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 402 firms from the 17 sectors were randomly
selected for the survey.
</P>
<P>
The OPS also raised the issue of productivity in the
workplace, saying that "almost all industrial groups recorded a
decline in labor productivity during the survey period".
</P>
<P>
Contrary to the government announced macroeconomic
improvement, the OPS said "the economy is still in recession" on
the macro scene.
</P>
<P>
The recession is made worse by poor infrastructure -- power,
water, telephone, and shortage of utilities like petroleum
products.
</P>
<P>
"There must be a real focus to address these problems,
including privatization and private participation in electric
supply" and special emphasis placed on building of
infrastructure, the memo said.
</P>
<P>
The businessmen also painted a dismal picture of the standard
of living of Nigerians, saying that the "poverty level has
degenerated".
</P>
<P>
Lamenting the very high cost of doing business, the POS called
for removal of excise duty on all products, reduction in port
charges and multiplicity of taxes.
</P>
<P>
It also called for removal of all bureaucratic bottlenecks and
effective/efficient implementation of incentives, as well as more
positive and concrete measures to enhance agricultural and food
production.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
