<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Reptile Virus Isolated in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- A research group at the
Institute of Hydrobiology of the Chinese Academy of Sciences has
successfully isolated the virus which gave rise to last year's
epidemic of sinohelicoprion, a reptile living only in China.
</P>
<P>
As reptile virus research is relatively incomplete compared to
the other vertebrates, it's the first time in the world that
scientists have been able to isolate a virus from a reptile.
</P>
<P>
Scientists believe the discovery has not only clarified the
root cause of the fulminating-type epidemic disease, but also
created a new approach to looking for the cause and prevention of
disease from the perspective of molecular biology and immunity.
</P>
<P>
Sinohelicoprion breeding has spread rapidly in China due to its
value in medicine and nutrition. But the breakout of epidemic
disease last year sharply reduced its production.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, half of sinohelicoprion breeding farms
were reportedly affected, with the mortality rate reaching 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
Scientists who analyzed the virus specimen under electron
microscopes said the virus, globular in shape and 30 nanometers in
diameter, has no cyst-membrane. Five polypeptides construct its
basic protein.
</P>
<P>
Researchers said that at the moment they are carrying out
further pathology research on various levels of tissues, cells,
and molecules as well as immunity research.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
