<HEADLINE> Street-Lighting Project to Brighten Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Municipal Government of
China's capital recently launched a project to make major streets
and roads three times brighter in the next five to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The municipal office in charge of power supply has upgraded the
lights in Tian'anmen Square and those along East and West Chang'an
streets, the city's most famous transportation trunk line.
</P>
<P>
Four groups of halogen lights have been erected in Tian'anmen
Square. Each group has a lighting capacity of 46 kilowatts.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, lighting will also be improved on five
major east-west streets, three major north-south streets and the
three ring roads.
</P>
<P>
The last step will be to "light up each and every street and
road in Beijing," an official said. There are 83,000 street lights
in the city.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, many Chinese cities have received a face lift
with illumination projects. For example, the night scene of the
Bunds in Shanghai, China's industrial and commercial center, has
become a major attraction for tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
