<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Against Mideast Peace Process: Iranian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Iranian supreme leader Ali
Khamenei said here today Iran is against the Middle East peace
process because it is "unjust and illogical."
</P>
<P>
In his inaugural speech to the eighth summit of the
Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC), Khamenei said, "our
opposition to the so-called Middle East peace process is because
it is unjust, arrogant, contemptuous and finally illogical."
</P>
<P>
He said, "the imposed principle of 'land for peace' means that
the Zionists (Israelis) would return the lands of all neighboring
countries, provided that we accept that Palestine belongs to
them. What could be more unjust than these words?"
</P>
<P>
He said that it is the time that the Islamic world should
give more support to the frontline states who are waging heroic
struggle against Israel, the usurper of Arab lands, while
expressing his solute to the resistance movement in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian leader called on the Islamic world to close ranks,
stressing that "what can the United States do vis-a-vis the
united front of the Islamic countries ranging from Indonesia to
North Africa?"
</P>
<P>
He then blasted the U.S. for creating discord and disunity in
the Islamic world in order to make the Islamic nations fear each
other. He declared, "Iran poses no threat to any Islamic
country," apparently referring to the Gulf nations.
</P>
<P>
He termed the U.S. military presence in the Gulf as "improper"
as the Gulf, "an Islamic sea and an important source of energy
for the entire world," has turned insecurity. At the same time,
he suggested that the OIC deploy forces from Islamic countries to
preserve and safeguard peace and security in the region.
</P>
<P>
On the OIC performance, Khamenei said that the world today
has more serious expectations from the organization as compared
with those of the past. "This organization can be the symbol of
true unity of the Muslim countries in the face of events and
common interests. It can speak on behalf of its members, make
demands, carry out requisite measures, and enjoy their financial,
economic, and political backing," he explained.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the organization can play an active role in the
economic area and to translate the idea of the common Islamic
market from a far-fetched dream to a reality.
</P>
<P>
He also stated that the OIC should become the sixth permanent
member of the U.N. Security Council as it is the representative of
55 nations with a total population of over one billion.
</P>
<P>
The eighth OIC summit is the largest ever get-together of the
55-member Islamic body since it was established 27 years
ago. The seat of Afghanistan is left vacant because the OIC was
divided as to who should represent the country. Afghan President
Burhanuddin Rabbani attends the meeting as an observer.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 presidents, vice-presidents, emirs and crown
princes are present at the summit, together with thousands of
officials and representatives.
</P>
<P>
The three-day summit commits itself to promoting "dignity,
dialogue and participation" in the Islamic world and is expected
to address a wide range of issues faced by the Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the summit, the OIC foreign ministers held a two-day
meeting on December 6-7 to debate and give endorsement to more
than 140 draft resolutions. The drafts will be further discussed
at the summit for final approval.
</P>
<P>
Moroccan Prime Minister Abdul Latif Al-Filali, whose country
hosted the seventh Islamic summit three years ago, also made a
speech at the session and Iran's President Mohammad Khatami
followed him to address the session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0159 </DOCNO>
