<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea to Save Banks Through Governmental Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 9 (Xinhua) -- South Korean government will pour
huge money into two ailing banks -- Korean First Bank and Seoul
Bank -- within this week to boost their paid-in-capital to the
adequacy level required by the Bank for International Settlements
(BIS).
</P>
<P>
Finance and Economy Ministry officials said the investment,
amounting to 1.18 trillion won (about 886 million U.S. dollars)
for each, would return the two banks to health, as their capital
will represent eight percent of risk-weighted asset, the
BIS-required capital adequacy ratio.
</P>
<P>
As their paid-in-capital will rise from 820 billion won (about
615.6 million dollars) each to two trillion won (about 1,5 billion
dollars) each, the two banks will be able to dissolve the
insolvency fears raised during the negotiations with the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) about its rescue credit.
</P>
<P>
The IMF negotiators demanded the two banks be closed if they
fail to improve their paid-in-capital up to eight percent in four
months by stringent restructuring.
</P>
<P>
With the investment, the government's interest in the two banks
will increase 59 percent of their equity capital.
</P>
<P>
In return, the government will require the banks to follow a
stringent restructuring regime, including the layoffs of more than
1,500 workers each over the next one and half to two years.
</P>
<P>
In addition, they will have to slash wages by at least 10
percent for employees and 30 percent for officers, and shut down
some 40 branches each, in addition to disposal of "unnecessary"
property. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
