<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Minister Threatens to Close Unethical </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 9 (Xinhua) -- In the wake of mounting public
condemnation of unethical scenes being broadcast by local
television, Lebanese Information Minister Bassem Al-Sabaa
has threatened to close down sinning networks.
</P>
<P>
"Why, in one month, were a number of programs broadcast on
rape, homosexuality, premartial sex and incest, as if this was
the true problem in Lebanon?" local newspaper the Daily Star
today quoted Sabaa as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The goal, not to raise social issues, may have involved
politics or advertising, especially since none of the episodes
provided specific, scientific solutions," he added.
</P>
<P>
Several programs had shown "the worst image of Lebanese
society in a very short period of time", while movies and
programs with scenes of sexuality were being broadcast at
inappropriate hours, he said.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri recently hosted a meeting of TV
station chiefs at his home.
</P>
<P>
He said that abiding by the law was a prerequisite for media
institutions and if they continued to show little respect for
legislation, he would have to intervene and hold them
accountable.
</P>
<P>
Christian and Muslim clerics have already started organizing
campaigns against unethical programs and press stories and
pictures.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese President Elias Hrawi on more than one occasion
brought up the issue, calling for more control and decency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
