<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Service Sector to Help Laid-off Workers (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
While keeping public ownership as the foundation of the
socialist economic system, China needs to develop the sector of
mixed ownership and the non-public sector, the commentary
continued.
</P>
<P>
Estimates show that self-employed and private businesses
provided about 13.9 million new jobs from 1991 to 1995, accounting
for 40 percent of the total newly created job opportunities in
cities, the story said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this century, the service sector will take up
nearly one-third of the total employment and will create 11
million new jobs annually, according to the story.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai had 700 enterprises go bankrupt in the last few years,
laying off nearly one million workers. New businesses in the
service sector provided 800,000 of those with jobs.
</P>
<P>
Part-time jobs should be encouraged and are expected to
increase, the commentary said.
</P>
<P>
The service sector still has great potential, said an official
from the State Planning Commission, and is lagging behind in some
areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the traditional service enterprises should develop
in such professional and society-oriented modern businesses as
transportation, security services, accounting, finance and public
relations, the commentary concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
