<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Weaker on Asian Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar
continued to fall today, sliding to a new four-year low of 66.7
U.S. cents in early European trading, pressured by troubled Asian
markets.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished the local session at 66.9 U.S.
cents, from 67.11 cents yesterday, and continued to drift lower in
early offshore trading. It was last at these levels in December
1993.
</P>
<P>
Traders say little respite is in store for the local currency
now that it has breached the critical 66.8 U.S. cent level.
</P>
<P>
St. George Bank foreign exchange trading manager Stuart Moore
said the market was mixed today, with short covering pushing the
Australian dollar to the day's high of 67.37 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
"But then with the Asian markets opening, the Korean won
weakening, and the Indonesian rupiah weakening, the Aussie slowly
drifted back off," Moore said.
</P>
<P>
Moore said 66.8 U.S. cents was seen as a critical support level
and a breach could lead to a quick run to the downside.
</P>
<P>
Also today, Westpac general manager of economic planning and
strategy Bill Evans said the Australian dollar could fall to 65
cents against the greenback.
</P>
<P>
"Our research indicates that probably the fair value for the
dollar at the moment is about 68, 69 cents but the research also
shows that in extreme times, and we have an extreme time at the
moment, it can fall 4 or 5 cents below that fair value."
</P>
<P>
Against the Japanese yen this evening, the Australian dollar
finished at 87.24 from 87.05 yesterday. It was at 1.1983 from
1.1957 against the Deutsche mark.  
</P>
</TEXT>
