<HEADLINE> President Orders to Help Flood-Ridden Kenyans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi has instructed relevant government departments to move
swiftly in Northeastern Province which has been affected by
floods, the East African Standard reported today.
</P>
<P>
Moi called for sufficient supplies of food and medicine to the
affected areas where have for the last few weeks been badly
affected by heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
He said that no one should die as a result of the floods which
have claimed dozens of lives and displaced hundreds of families.
</P>
<P>
At least 12 people have reportedly died at Garusa and
Kumahumato areas of the flooded province over the past two days
following an outbreak of diarrhoea.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of others are said to be suffering from the same
disease and starvation-related ailments due to the acute shortage
of food and clean water.
</P>
<P>
Garissa District Commissioner Ali Mbwarali was quoted as
saying that he had asked for assistance from Nairobi for the
ailing and starving residents.
</P>
<P>
He, however, said that all major roads had been made
impassable by heavy rains, hindering the delivery of humanitarian
aid to the local residents.
</P>
<P>
Former Cabinet Minister Hussein Maalim Mohamed yesterday
donated food and medical supplies worth 60,000 U.S. Dollars to
victims of Tana River floods.
</P>
<P>
The British government has given Kenya some 500,000 Dollars to
fund emergency relief operations in Northeastern Province of
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian government has offered Kenya two military
transport planes to assist in airlifting emergency food supplies
to flood-affected areas.
</P>
<P>
The on-going nomination of parliamentary and civic candidates
in the province were yesterday delayed due to floods and
inaccessibility.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's Electoral Commission Chairman Samuel Kivuitu said
Monday that some returning officers and clerks were stranded in
parts of Tana River District which could not be reached by road.
</P>
<P>
Arrangements had been made to hire two government helicopters
to transport the documents and personnel to the affected areas
and it is hoped that the exercise would go on as planned, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The torrential storms and floods blamed on the El Nino
phenomenon have forced the Kenyan government to declare Coast and
Northeastern provinces disaster zones.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations estimates that some 300,000 people are
affected and desperately need relief food in the East African
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
