<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Mining Industry Lays Off 2,000 Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's mining industry,
hard-pressed by free-falling metal prices, has retrenched over
2,000 workers this year and many more jobs might be lost next
year if prices remain depressed, The Herald daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Poor prices of minerals, particularly gold, nickel and copper,
have strained operations forcing mining companies to cut costs
through retrenchments.
</P>
<P>
President of the Chambers of Mines John Nixon said the 2,000
retrenched workers included only those workers retrenched by big
mines.
</P>
<P>
It is difficult to get the exact numbers of other workers who
were laid off by small-scale and informal sector miners.
</P>
<P>
Nixon told the paper Monday the market was unlikely to recover
in the shorter-term, spelling more problems for mining companies.
</P>
<P>
The low gold price, which hit the lowest this year in the last
12 years, has already forced the closure of some marginal mines.
Larger companies have had to streamline their operations to
remain in business, Nixon said, adding noted Ashanti Gold Mine
Company is also selling six of its smaller mines in this country
as it focuses on larger mines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
