<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Down After Lackluster Day's Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
closed slightly down after a lackluster day's trade today as the
traditional wind-down for the Christmas/New Year season began to
take hold.
</P>
<P>
A softer U.S. market and stronger performances on Monday night
in Asian economies failed to influence investors, with only light
trading in local stocks.
</P>
<P>
Henderson Charlton Jones dealer Scott Emms said the local
bourse took little direction from overseas markets today.
</P>
<P>
"Our overall market was terribly light on volume," he said. "I
think a lot of people are winding down for the Christmas period."
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index closed down 4.2 points at 2582.8 while
the All Resources dropped 0.6 points to 1127.2 and the All
Industrials 8.6 points to 4410.1.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector, global miner Rio Tinto led the mining
stocks closing up 39.3 cents while BHP lost 8 cents and MIM 1
cent.
</P>
<P>
Gold also fell further last night and was trading 1.2 U.S.
dollars down at 286.5 U.S. dollars in Sydney but, against all
recent trends, the index closed up 3.7 points to 877.8.
</P>
<P>
While industrial stocks closed generally softer, News Corp.,
Telstra and Lend Lease finished the day in positive territory.
</P>
<P>
The major banks all fared badly, with ANZ closing down 7.5
cents, National Australia Bank shaving off 15.5 cents,
Commonwealth losing 12 cents and Westpac dropping 5 cents.
</P>
<P>
At the close of trading today, national turnover was 276.48
million shares worth 751.31 million Australian dollars (503.37
million U.S. dollars) with rises of 506 outnumbering falls of 497.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
