<HEADLINE> China Exports Large Railway Crane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, December 9 (Xinhua) -- A railway crane with hydraulic
arms and a lifting capacity of 100 tons has been exported to be
used on the Tanzania-Zambia Railway. This is the largest railway
crane China has ever exported.
</P>
<P>
The Lanzhou Rolling Stock Plant won the purchase bid for a
project organized last year by China's State Economic and Trade
Commission and the China Civil Engineering Group Corp.
</P>
<P>
This is one of six projects to assist the Tanzania-Zambia
Railway. The crane will be used in rescue operations, loading and
unloading, and tunnel work.
</P>
<P>
Under normal conditions, the crane can lift 100-ton cargo a
maximum height of 15 meters at a speed of 4 meters a minute. It
can be driven at six kilometers per hour with a pull force of 300
tons.
</P>
<P>
The plant has sold 10 such cranes to Chinese iron and steel
producers and railway bureaus.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 08:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Peace Group Releases Report to Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli human rights
group B'tselem released a report today to mark the 10th
anniversary of the intifada, or Palestinian uprising against
Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
Since the onset of the intifada on December 9, 1987, through
November 30, 1997, 1,346 Palestinians were killed by Israeli
troops or security forces, and another 131 Palestinians killed
by Israeli civilians, while 256 Israeli civilians and 127
Israeli soldiers were killed by Palestinians, the report said.
</P>
<P>
From December 1987 until the signing of Oslo accords in
September 1993, 1,087 Palestinians were killed by Israeli
soldiers and 75 others killed by Israeli civilians. In the same
period, 101 Israeli civilians and 59 Israeli soldiers were killed
by Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
From the signing of Oslo accords in September 1993 to November
1997, 259 Palestinians were killed by Israeli soldiers and 56
others by Israeli civilians. In the same period, 155 Israeli
civilians and 68 Israeli soldiers and policemen were killed by
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
This means that since the signing of Oslo accords, more
Israeli soldiers and civilians have been killed than during the
1987-1993 period when the intifada was at its peak, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
B'tselem said that while no Palestinians have been deported
from the Palestinian territories since the end of 1992, Israel
has destroyed the homes of 81 families of accused assailants
from the end of 1992 through the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Palestinian lawmakers marked the 10th anniversary of
intifada Monday by calling for struggle until achieving
statehood. Members of the Palestinian Council marked the intifada
by opening a meeting in Ramallah, West Bank, with a moment of
silence in memory of the Palestinians killed in the uprising.
</P>
<P>
While the council refrained from issuing an official
statement, members debated the intifada's significance in the
context of current peace moves. The consensus was that
Palestinians should continue their struggle until they achieve
independent statehood.
</P>
<P>
Council member Marwan Barghouti, Secretary of the mainstream
Palestinian movement Fatah in the West Bank, said the intifada's
goals have not been achieved and the uprising must continue in
spirit. He warned Israel that if the peace process breaks down,
"the intifada will return, using different methods and
techniques." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
