<HEADLINE> Stocks Rebound in Tokyo on Hopes of Using Public Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Tokyo stock prices rebounded
today on reports that Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto has
instructed the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) to consider
using some government bonds to stabilize the financial system.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First Section
of the Tokyo Stock Exchange jumped 554.94 points, or by 3.44
percent from Monday's close to 16,686.51.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the First Section came to an estimated 460 million
shares, up from Monday's 425.02 million shares.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index, covering all issues
on the First Section, advanced 26.76 points, or by 2.19 percent to
1,248.07.
</P>
<P>
Failed Hokkaido Takushoku Bank was today's most actively traded
issue.
</P>
<P>
Market participants welcomed the news that the LDP will
consider using 10 trillion Japanese yen (about 76.7 billion
U.S. dollars) in public money to restore confidence in the
financial system.
</P>
<P>
The reports prompted expectations that the government may also
map out effective economic stimulus measures, giving a boost to a
broad range of issues, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,329 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
outweighed losers 802 to 305, with 158 issues unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
