<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Service Sector Expected to Help More Laid-off Workers (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Laid-off Chinese workers should
find new jobs in the flourishing service sector, stressed a
commentary in today's People's Daily, the country's leading
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
State-funded enterprises had been the mainstay of job
opportunities in the planned economy, but are now faced with
surplus workers, the commentary said.
</P>
<P>
There has been a steady decline in the number of newly employed
workers in state-owned enterprises -- 72 percent of the total in
cities in 1978, 61 percent in 1985 and 34 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Employees in the state economy accounted for 64.1 percent of
all Chinese urban workers in 1996, compared to 78.3 percent in
1978. This means that state-run businesses have laid off 25
million workers. In addition, three million lay-offs are expected
each year through 2000, according to the commentary.
</P>
<P>
In developed countries, the industrial sector usually provides
18 percent of the jobs. In 1994, for the first time in China,
there were fewer jobs in the industrial sector than those in the
service sector. The industrial sector's need for workers is
expected to continue to decline, the commentary said.
</P>
<P>
Readjustment of the economic structure will provide new job
opportunities, economics experts pointed out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
