<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Employers Urged to End Sexual </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 9 (Xinhua) -- A Zimbabwean minister said
employers should make an effort to weed out sexual harassment in
the workplace in order to tap the potential of female employees.
</P>
<P>
Public service, Labour and Social Welfare Minister Florence
Chitauro told a meeting on 16 days of activism against gender
violence said every third woman in Zimbabwe's workplace was
sexually Harassed.
</P>
<P>
This makes sexual harassment the most prevalent form of gender
based victimization of women.
</P>
<P>
Sexual harassment not only affected women's productivity, but
also their health and social lives, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"Unless and until sexual harassment in all its diabolic forms
is reported and companies and authorities respond to it as a
crime violating the rights of working women, it cannot be
eliminated," said Chitauro.
</P>
<P>
The participants to the meeting implored Chitauro to introduce
legislation that explicitly condemns sexual harassment and
prescribes penalties against offenders.
</P>
<P>
They said sexual harassment did not only affect women in
formal employment, but those in the informal sector as well.
</P>
<P>
Chitauro said respective companies should come up with clear
policies against sexual harassment and establish a transparent
reporting procedure. 
</P>
