<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Foreign Debt Situation Healthy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"All the indices indicate that China has been generally
successful in the administration of foreign debt," Li said.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign debt has been expanding yearly since it began
borrowing overseas in 1979. The amount of foreign debt China
borrowed totaled 240.24 billion U.S. dollars between 1985, the
first year when official statistics were available, and 1996. Over
the years China has maintained a good debt-repayment record,
paying back 169.72 billion U.S. dollars in principal and interest.
</P>
<P>
The expanding foreign debt has prompted the Chinese government
to adopt a series of policies and regulations to strengthen debt
management to improve its overall situation, including the
introduction last year of a quota control system for medium- and
long-term overseas loans.
</P>
<P>
While gradually encouraging qualified enterprises to raise
funds on their own in the international capital market, China will
further reform its system in accordance with such international
practices as imposing a ceiling on financial institutions'
outstanding value of medium- and long-term foreign debt and
enforcing a credit rating system among institutions raising funds
overseas, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Economists warn that foreign debts are "double-edged": while an
appropriate amount of foreign debt may effectively boost economic
growth when used efficiently, excessive foreign debt will result
in a crisis if improperly used.
</P>
<P>
Based on this understanding, China should strive hard to
control the size of its foreign debt and make more efficient use
of the borrowed money, they suggested.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0210 </DOCNO>
