<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Province Has Satisfactory Grain Output After Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning Province in northeast
China harvested 13 million tons of grain this year despite a
severe drought, official sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The harvest did not come easily. As the country's oldest
heavy-industrial base, the province's agricultural sector has
been considered a bottleneck for local economic growth since the
1980s, with nearly half of its grain and vegetable supplies
coming from other provinces.
</P>
<P>
Strategies have been worked out, giving equal importance to
agricultural development and the prevailing industrial sector, as
Wen Shizhen, governor of Liaoning, said that agricultural
development should be treated as a top priority.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning has allocated 1.6 billion yuan annually to aid the
agricultural sector. The past five years have seen improvements to
120,000 hectares of low-yielding farmland and expansion to 250,000
hectares of irrigated fields.
</P>
<P>
Recent efforts to improve flood- and drought-resistant
capabilities of the seven major reservoirs in the central part of
the province have helped the province increase at least 2 billion
kilograms of grain.
</P>
<P>
For the last five years, Liaoning's grain output has exceeded
15 million tons, which is considered more than
self-sufficient. Non-staple goods such as vegetables, fruits,
meat, eggs and aquatics reached 20 million tons this year, double
the figure of five years ago.
</P>
<P>
Benefited by rapid growth in the rural economy, half of the
province's two million impoverished people have been lifted above
the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
Official figures also show that the output value from township
enterprises accounting for 40 percent of the province's total
industrial sector and this year's per-capita annual income in the
rural areas averages over 2,300 yuan (about 277 U.S. dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
