<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Foreign Debt Situation Healthy  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The status of China's foreign
debt is healthy, with all major indices well within established
international safety limits, officials and experts agree.
</P>
<P>
Both the size and risk potential of China's foreign debts have
been brought under effective control in tandem to improve the debt
structure since 1993 when China began to implement macro-control
economic policies, an official of the State Administration of
Foreign Exchange (SAFE) told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Official figures indicate that China's foreign debts have
entered a period of reasonable growth, with the increase in
outstanding value up less than 10 percent in 1996 and 8.3 percent
in the first half of 1997, compared to an average 25 percent for
the 1986-1990 period and 15.2 percent for the 1991-1995 period.
</P>
<P>
In terms of structure, short-term debts accounted for barely
11.5 percent of China's foreign debt of 118.64 billion U.S.
dollars at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
"China's foreign debt is appropriate to its economic strength
and its position of balance of international payments," Li Yang,
director of the Financial Research Center of the Chinese Academy
of Social Sciences, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
In another analysis, the three major indices tracking the
health of a country's foreign debt situation are all well below
internationally accepted levels.
</P>
<P>
China's ratio of outstanding foreign debt to annual foreign
exchange earnings was 75.6 percent at the end of 1996, much lower
than the conventional standard of 100 percent. The indebtedness
rate, or the ratio of annual repayment of debt principal and
interest to foreign exchange income of the same year, was at 6.7
percent, compared with the recognized standard of 20 percent. The
other index, the debt-servicing ratio, measured by the result of a
country's gross domestic product divided by the outstanding value
of its foreign debt, was 14.3 percent, far below the average for
developing nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
