<P>
In an informal meeting with the press here, visiting U.S.
Commerce Secretary William M. Daley, however, expressed hope about
receiving an improved offer from India which may end the logjam.
</P>
<P>
Daley, who held talks with his Indian counterpart B.B. Ramaiah
on Monday, said the U.S. side had decided to continue negotiating
with the Indian side even after the World Trade Organization (WTO)
sets up a panel to look into the issue.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. is also pressing for reduction in import duty
on a variety of items before the two countries could arrive at a
compromise to end the dispute over quantitative restrictions on
imports.
</P>
<P>
When asked why the U.S. was taking a rigid stand while others
like the European Union, Canada, Japan and Australia have accepted
the six-year phaseout offered by India, Daley simply said his
country's position is different.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
