<HEADLINE> Ukraine Army Fulfills 1997 Development Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Ukrainian army has fulfilled
its development plan for 1997, Vasily Sobkov, army commander, said
here today at a press conference marking Ukraine's first Army Day.
</P>
<P>
Despite the economic difficulty it has been experiencing since
its founding six years ago, Sobkov said, the Ukrainian army has
not lost its combat effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
He said the army now has 200,000 men, including 40,000
officers, and six academies, two trainers divisions and three
warrant officers schools.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Sobkov pointed out, the army still has big
numbers of commissioned positions unfilled. When Ukraine was first
independent, 47 percent of the officers were Russians. Now with
those Russians gone, he said, only 80 percent of the positions of
officers and warrant officers are filled.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that the army's 1998 technology and equipment
development plan will soon be publicized.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine has a defense force of 370,000 men. Besides a military
construction and development program to be implemented before the
year 2005, the government also mapped out the plan for the army at
the beginning of 1997 so as to help its professionalization and
modernization. 
</P>
