<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Crop Production to Fall This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's crop production is
expected to fall by between 1.34 percent and 5.61 percent this
year due to the severe drought, an official of the Ministry of
Agriculture said.
</P>
<P>
Director General of Food Crop of the Agriculture Ministry
Chairil Anwar Rasahan was quoted today by Antara News Agency as
saying that rice production this year was expected to reach 49.14
million tons, falling by 3.85 percent from last year's harvest of
51.10 million tons.
</P>
<P>
"This year's production will fail to surpass the initial target
of 52.19 million tons," Chairil said.
</P>
<P>
According to data from the Central Bureau of Statistics, corn
production is estimated to drop by 1.34 percent to 9.18 million
tons this year from 9.31 million tons last year.
</P>
<P>
This year's soybean production is also predicted to fall by
3.82 percent to 1.46 million tons from 1.52 million tons in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Peanut production is expected to drop by 3.7 percent to 710,517
tons compared to last year's 737,815 tons.
</P>
<P>
Green beans production is expected to reach 284,521 tons,
falling by 5.61 percent from 301,421 tons last year.
</P>
<P>
Chairil did not specify the cause of the drop in most food crop
production, saying only that the long drought had played a
significant role.
</P>
<P>
He also said the government will work hard to maintain
self-sufficiency in rice by, among other things, increasing the
productivity of the country's rice fields, promoting the use of
quality seeds, preventing the spread of rice pests, and developing
farmers' awareness of the importance of agricultural machinery.
</P>
</TEXT>
