expected to be 15 billion U.S. dollars this year, a 30 percent
rise over 1996.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's agricultural trade balance will enjoy a surplus of 11
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Trade deficit of Argentina reached 3.54 billion
dollars by October, contrasting with the surplus of 271 million
dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Economy said that the huge deficit was due to
an extraordinary growth on imports, 26 percent more than last year.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Exports of mango from Costa Rica are expected to
reach 14.3 million dollars by the end of this year, a 64.4 percent
increase over 1996, the Ministry of Agriculture and Cattle said.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica looks forward to selling 62.4 million dollars of the
tropical fruit by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The Mexican Stock Exchange ranks the world's
first in profits this year, with 41.5 percent increase, followed
by Switzerland with 39.2 percent, Italy 33.3 percent and the
United States 32.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The Ministry of Agriculture in Brazil plans to
irrigate one million hectares of land all over the country, with
100,000 hectares to be irrigated over the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
The northwestern state of Rio Grande Do Norte will be mainly
benefited by this project.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay's imports of capital assets soared 18.4
percent in the past 12 months, ending September, the Central Bank
said.
</P>
<P>
Imports of transportation equipment rose by 22 percent and
industrial machinery 18.5 percent in the period. 
