<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Manila Wins Initial Success in Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Philippine government agents
have arrested 28 kidnap suspects since Friday, giving heat to the
latest anti-kidnapping campaign launched at the beginning of the
month.
</P>
<P>
Government officials said the 28 suspects belong to three
kidnap syndicates. Their fall solved 80 percent of the
kidnap-for-ransom cases reported across the country this year.
</P>
<P>
"We will not tolerate further kidnappings in this country. This
is a quick response and warning to all who defy the law," Justice
Secretary Teofisto Guingona said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an official with the Presidential Anti-Crime
Commission revealed that the national police are monitoring the
activities of some other gangs believed to be involved in
kidnappings.
</P>
<P>
Guingona said the nabbed suspects include the kidnap-slayers of
Gordon Tan and Ignacio Ong Jr., two young Filipino-Chinese
businessmen killed on November 24 and December 2 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The murder of Tan and Ong prompted the Filipino-Chinese in
Metro Manila to stage a series of protests. In a strongly-worded
open letter to President Fidel Ramos, they called for the
immediate stop of such kidnapping cases in the country.
</P>
<P>
"we are aghast. We fear for our lives and those of our beloved
ones," they wrote, saying President Ramos is the only one who can
help them.
</P>
<P>
"The kidnap-for-ransom syndicates have hurled a direct
challenge at your leadership and at your law enforcers' capability
to catch not only the criminals but their masterminds", they said.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics released by anti-kidnapping
organizations, about 950 people were kidnapped between 1993 and
1996 and 85 of them murdered. In the first 10 months of this year,
193 more were abducted and at least 9 million U.S. dollars have
been paid in ransom.
</P>
<P>
Not only has the problem worsened considerably but the
kidnappers have also become more and more brazen and daring,
taking victims right from inside their business establishments and
homes, in broad daylight and in busy thoroughfares too,
anti-kidnapping groups said.
</P>
<P>
The Filipino-Chinese attributed the rampage of kidnapping cases
to the incapacity of the military and the police. They said some
cops were kidnappers or protectors of abductors, citing that a
national police ID was recently found on a kidnapper's dead body.
</P>
<P>
However, the police accused the victims' families of failing to
cooperate with them. In fear that the victims might be killed by
the kidnappers, the victims' families usually do not report the
case to the police. Instead, they pay the ransom immediately,
giving no clues for the police to pursue the kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
Swamped by widespread criticism of his government's failure to
stop and solve kidnappings, President Ramos became angry and
turned the heat on his cabinet secretaries and police generals.
</P>
<P>
"I want results," Ramos told the secretaries of all law
enforcement agencies, scolding them for failing to cooperate well
with each other. He ordered the top leaders of the police and the
military to quickly map out a battle plan against kidnappers and
their own men engaged in kidnapping and other crimes.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, Philippine National Police chief Recaredo
Sarmiento tendered his resignation for the recent rash of
kidnappings. Ramos accepted his resignation, appointed a new
police chief and ordered the launching of the latest
anti-kidnapping campaign.
</P>
<P>
Since then policemen have been on 24-hour patrol in sensitive
areas in Metro Manila. Policemen working in neighboring provinces
also came to reinforce the forces in Manila as courts were urged
to speed up the prosecution of kidnapping cases and the execution
of convicted kidnappers facing death penalty.
</P>
<P>
The anti-kidnapping organizations commended the initial success
of the law enforcers. But they also called on the police to work
hard to arrest the masterminds of these kidnapping cases and have
them punished.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Eximbank Sets Up Chengdu Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Export-Import Bank of China
(China Eximbank) opened a representative office in Chengdu Monday,
capital of southwest China's Sichuan Province, according to
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the office, its sixth, following the bank's
offices in Dalian, Shanghai, Wuhan, Guangzhou and Xi'an, aims to
help bolster southwest China's exports of machinery and electronic
products.
</P>
<P>
Bank officials said the establishment of the Chengdu office
will help the bank to strengthen loan project investigation and
management in the region and also provide convenience for local
enterprises to get financial support from the Eximbank.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan Province and Chongqing Municipality are important
industrial bases in southwest China, with the exports of the
region's machinery and electronic items increasing by 32.3 percent
during 1987-1996 period, higher than the country's export growth
rate.
</P>
<P>
The Eximbank, one of China's three policy-oriented banks, was
established in 1994. It is designed to support the country's
export of high-tech and high-value products as well as complete
sets of equipment, the paper said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
