<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Finance Minister to Probe Central Bank Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will take action
against senior officials of the country's central bank found
responsible for mismanagement of the bank and foreign reserves,
according to the Bangkok Post today.
</P>
<P>
A special committee will be set up within days to investigate
the Bank of Thailand's management of public money loaned to
troubled finance firms, and the use of foreign reserves to defend
the baht, the newspaper quotes Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmanhaeminda as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
In mid-year the central bank poured a staggering 430 billion
baht (16.9 billion U.S. dollars) into a hopeless, secret bailout
attempt of debt-ridden finance companies, many of which were
closed down Monday, 100 billion baht (3.9 billion dollars) of
public money in assisting the ailing Bangkok Bank of Commerce, and
23 billion dollars or two-thirds of the country's foreign
reserves, into international markets to defend the baht.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin said officials involved must accept responsibility for
their actions.
</P>
<P>
He added that the government will change the law so that it
would limit the power of the central bank governor and his
deputies in deciding and implementing economic policies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
