<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Japanese Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Japanese newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Asahi, Yomiuri, Nihon Keizai:
</P>
<P>
-- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto instructed Liberal
Democratic Party executives Monday to consider a proposed
government expenditure of 10 trillion yen to stabilize the
nation's financial systems.
</P>
<P>
Asahi, Yomiuri, Mainichi, Nihon Keizai:
</P>
<P>
-- Japan's Fair Trade Commission announced Monday that the
revision of the Antimonopoly Law would take effect on December 17,
lifting the 50-year-old ban on establishing holding companies.
</P>
<P>
Yomiuri:
</P>
<P>
-- An agreement on 5 percent greenhouse gas emission cut from
the 1990 level will be sought at the U.N. climate change
conference in Kyoto which will end on December 10.
</P>
<P>
Nihon Keizai:
</P>
<P>
-- Public support for Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto's cabinet has plunged to a record-low of 35 percent, a
survey shows. 
</P>
