<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Closure of 56 Thai Finance Firms Welcomed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government's decision
to close 56 of the 58 suspended ailing finance firms has received
wide-spread support from both local and foreign business people
and analysts.
</P>
<P>
Most believe the step was, although painful, necessary and in
the right direction, according to the Bangkok Post today.
</P>
<P>
"The government announcement lifted some more of the black
cloud surrounding Thailand. It was a very positive move. It will
mean some short-term pain but a long-term gain for the whole Thai
economy," Paul Wanglee, chief strategist for Thailand at Goldman
Saches (Hong Kong), was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the closures mean that foreign investors are invited in
and bad management and companies are kicked out of business.
</P>
<P>
The Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) index strengthened Monday
in response to the announcement, rising 13.03 points (3.35
percent) to close at 401.80, with trading value of more than 3.5
billion baht (83.3 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The baht strengthened to 41.45 immediately after the
announcement, but gradually weakened to 42.20 on very high demand
for U.S. dollars from corporations.
</P>
<P>
Nikhil Srinivasan, vice president of equities at Morgan
Stanley, said the announcement seemed to point to a political will
to get the country back on the right track. Transparency,
equality, and willingness have all been shown in the announcement
and these are the things demanded by investors.
</P>
<P>
Khananphan Natanasen from Deutsche Morgan Grenfell said the
government had taken an impressive and tough decision, and this
was bound to boost confidence and could greatly assist efforts to
persuade foreign banks to roll over their loans extended to the
Thai private sector.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank's country director in Thailand J. Shivakumar
said Monday, "The World Bank strongly welcomes the decision" of
the Thai government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
