<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Expert Denies Engines Caused Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Engine failure was unlikely to be
the cause for the An-124 crash in the Russian city of Irkutsk on
December 6, a Ukrainian expert said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Vyacheslav Boguslaev, chairman of the Motor-Sich aircraft
engine manufacturing association which is based in the Ukrainian
city of Zaporozje, said Russian investigators have not found
sufficient evidence to prove engines made by Motor-Sich were the
cause for the crash.
</P>
<P>
The An-124 jumbo transport plane crashed in Irkutsk just a few
seconds after takeoff last Saturday, killing all on board and many
people in an apartment building the plane slammed into.
</P>
<P>
Russian television reported the number of casualties had risen
to about 60 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Boguslaev was furious with Yevegeni Shaposhnikov, the Russian
President's adviser on aviation matters. Shaposhnikov indicated
that Motor-sich engines were the cause even before Russia's
inquiry team led by Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin set off on
a fact-finding mission to Irkutsk.
</P>
<P>
The Motor-Sich chairman said Shaposhnikov gave confusing
information about the crash in his televised speech.
</P>
<P>
"Shaposhnikov said two of the four engines failed, but later he
said the four engines failed simultaneously," said Boguslaev.
</P>
<P>
He said engine performance did not depend solely on the
manufacturer, but also on those who maintained them. "Human error
was 99.9 percent the cause," he predicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
