<HEADLINE> Yeltsin to Meet Clinton on Arms Reduction Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
will meet United States President Bill Clinton here next year to
discuss the enactment of the Third Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's Press Secretary Sergi Yastrzhembsky made the
statement Monday in response to Clinton's signal for a meeting
with his Russian counterpart on the issue. The meeting would not
be this year, Yastezhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
Although Yeltsin called for contacts between Russian and
U.S. experts on the enactment of the treaty during his visit to
Sweden last week, Yastrzhembsky said, summit talks on the issue
would be a totally different matter.
</P>
<P>
He said at the moment it was still difficult to set a specific
date for the meeting. However, he noted, it was right to say it
should take place after Russian State Duma endorsed the Second
Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty.
</P>
<P>
The Second Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty was signed by Russia
and the United States in 1993. The U.S. Senate approved it in
1996. The Duma, however, still retains its negative attitude
toward it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
