<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Drug Lords Look for New Ways to Move Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Colombian drug cartels have
been searching for new ways to transport cocaine from production
regions to markets, a report from the U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency
(DEA) said today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted by the local daily La Republica said that
drug lords are using maritime routes from Panama to Guatemala
through the Caribbean Sea, instead of land.
</P>
<P>
Alternate routes have been explored since the Costa Rican
government seized about seven tons of cocaine over the past eight
months, said the DEA.
</P>
<P>
The United States has put pressure on the governments of the
Caribbean Islands and Central American countries to authorize
operations of ships and planes, as well as DEA's agents inside
their territorial waters and air space.
</P>
<P>
Several nations of the Caribbean and Central America have
agreed with the United States on the matter, but oppositions of
Costa Rica say the U.S. pressure is against the constitution.
</P>
<P>
The report said that drug cartels, specially those of Medellin
and Cali in Colombia dismantled by the police, have become
consortium of drug trafficking, well organized to produce, sell
and recycle the huge revenues earned in the illegal business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
