<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment In Argentina Escalates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Foreign capital in
Argentina has reached 52 billion dollars since 1994, the Andean
Foundation reported today.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the country attracted 17 billion dollars worth of
investment much of which has gone into the fastest growing
economic sectors of Argentina, such as the automobile industry,
food, chemicals,telecommunications, banks and insurance.
</P>
<P>
The latest report of the foundation says that 87 percent of the
total foreign capital in Argentina is concentrated in the
industrial sectors of oil, natural gas, power, mining and
supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
Among the major investors in the South American country, the
United States has the lion's share of 37.4 percent of the
total. Others on top of the list are Spain with 21.6 percent,
Canada with 6.7 percent, Chile with 6.3 percent, and France with
5.4 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
