<HEADLINE> CPC Leader Meets CPV General-Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 8 (Xinhua)-- China and Vietnam can properly
solve the problems in bilateral ties as long as the two sides
far-sightedly take into account the whole situation and the
fundamental interests of the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made here Monday by Li Ruihuan, a Standing
Committee member of the Political Bureau of the Communist Party of
China (CPC) Central Committee, during his meeting with Do Muoi,
general-secretary of the Central Committee of the Communist Party
of Vietnam (CPV).
</P>
<P>
"We firmly believe that through the joint efforts of the two
countries, bilateral ties would be consolidated in the new
century," Li said.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the two countries have maintained frequent
high-level exchanges and held similar and identical views on many
major international issues, he said.
</P>
<P>
Economic and trade cooperation, as well as exchanges in the
sectors of science, technology and culture between China and
Vietnam have been strengthened, he added.
</P>
<P>
Muoi said that China's current situation is encouraging, and
China's success in the modernization development has made great
contributions to the progressive cause of mankind.
</P>
<P>
He expressed satisfaction with the development of the relations
between the two parties and two countries, saying that the
historical problems between the two countries should and could be
solved through negotiation.
</P>
<P>
Li arrived here on December 7 for a four-day official good-will
visit to Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
