<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qinghuangdao Witnesses Rapid Growth in Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGHUANGDAO, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Official statistics show
that a total of 6.97 million Chinese and foreign tourists visited
the north China port city of Qinghuangdao during the first ten
months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Tourists spent nearly 100 million yuan on park admission fees,
making over 32.3 million US dollars in foreign exchange, up 67.8
percent on the 1996 period. The city's tourism revenues for the
January-October period grew eight percent to 2.7 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Qinghuangdao, which is home to a number of natural scenic sites
and places of historical interest, has extended great effort since
1995 to transform itself into one of China's major tourism
destinations.
</P>
<P>
The city's ambitious program during the first three quarters of
this year includes the establishment of 16 training programs
for tour guides and hotel workers. Some 1,300 people have
participated in related programs.
</P>
<P>
Qinghuangdao has also allocated substantial funding to
construct four parks covering 70,000 sq.m., with the city's green
coverage growing by 337,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
Efforts have also been made to protect and develop scenic sites
along the Great Wall.
</P>
<P>
This year Qinghuangdao has established business relations with
more than 10 overseas travel agencies and opened chartered flights.
</P>
<P>
A total of 75,960 foreign tourists visited Qinghuangdao during
the first 10 months of the year, up 13 percent on the 1996
period. The annual number of foreign tourists visiting the city is
expected to grow to 100,000 within the near future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
