<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Pakistani-Indian Rapprochement Vital to Regional Peace, Development (1)  by Xu Yuenai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and India are facing
this year many uncertainties both on political and economic
fronts, especially on the much-talked issue of normalizing
bilateral relations between them.
</P>
<P>
The prospects of resuming bilateral talks, which gained
momentum with positive results in the first half of this year,
seem to be overshadowed by the latest political crises in the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that Pakistan's recent constitutional crisis
which had gripped the nation for almost four months and the
political turmoil in neighboring India which led to a change of
government could be anything but conducive to promoting the
rapprochement process.
</P>
<P>
For half a century, it has been a cherished dream of the
peoples of Pakistan and India to normalize bilateral relations by
resolving all outstanding issues including the Kashmir dispute.
</P>
<P>
The Kashmir dispute, the main obstacle to the normalization
process, has bedeviled the atmosphere of understanding and
cooperation between Pakistan and India and has sparked several
brutal armed conflicts between the two since their independence in
1947.
</P>
<P>
Before January 1994, Pakistan and India had held seven rounds
of foreign secretary-level talks. But due to their basic
differences on the issue of Jammu and Kashmir, the two countries
failed to make any important and practical headway.
</P>
<P>
After that the two South Asian nations virtually had no
political contact on all levels for three consecutive years. It
was in March this year the impasse in the strained relations was
broken as the two countries resumed their bilateral talks.
</P>
<P>
The major initiative taken by the two countries towards
rapprochement was widely welcomed by the international community.
More encouraging, neither Pakistan nor India laid down any
pre-conditions for their eighth round of foreign secretary-level
talks held in New Delhi at the end of March.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and India have held three rounds of bilateral talks
since March this year. The most encouraging one was the meeting on
May 12 between Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and then
Indian Prime Minister I.K. Gujral in Male, capital of the
Maldives, during which the two sides agreed to address all
outstanding issues of concern and set up a mechanism, including
working groups at appropriate levels, to address all the issues in
an integrated manner.
</P>
<P>
However, due to their differences on major issues, the meetings
between the two leaders on September 24 in New York and on October
25 in Edinburgh, Scotland, made no major progress.
</P>
<P>
It is still hard to predict when the two countries will resume
their talks or whether any breakthrough will be made in future
talks.
</P>
<P>
Observers here are of the view that improving the long-strained
bilateral relations between Pakistan and India is an economic
necessity for both countries and the South Asian region as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
Economic matters, especially cooperation in commerce and trade
for common development, have become a top priority in
international relations today.
</P>
<P>
For developing countries like Pakistan and India, there is a
compelling need to spend less on armaments and more on social and
economic development.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, half a century after their independence,
Pakistan and India are still locked in confrontation over the
Kashmir issue. Successive governments of the two countries have
perpetuated this insecurity by diverting valuable resources needed
for alleviating poverty and ending social injustice to armament.
</P>
<P>
Observers here note, however, that despite their long-standing
dispute over the Kashmir issue, both Pakistan and India are now
under increasing strong domestic and global pressure to move
towards peace, friendship and cooperation with each other.
</P>
<P>
The leadership in the two countries have time and again
stressed the urgency to improve the living condition of their
peoples by alleviating poverty.
</P>
<P>
There is no doubt that only in a tension-free environment can
the two countries divert their scarce resources to development in
social and economic sectors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Pakistani-Indian Rapprochement Vital to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As far as Pakistan is concerned, it is faced with such a
critical resource crunch that its total national income is unable
to support two principal items of expenditure, namely, the debt
servicing and defense. Therefore, it faces severe chronological
budget and trade deficits.
</P>
<P>
The only way to overcome its growing trade gap is for Pakistan
to increases its export. Revitalizing the economy, therefore, has
become the top priority for the present Pakistani government.
</P>
<P>
India faces similar problems. Its target of seven percent
annual growth rate may not be achieved unless it is able to
attract large amounts of foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
The economic liberalization programs launched by the successive
Indian governments have generated a momentum for maximum
development process which can only be sustained if India promotes
regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Instability in the South Asian region has obstructed the
development of the member countries of the South Asian Association
for Regional Cooperation (SAARC), the main regional forum
established in 1985.
</P>
<P>
At the Ninth SAARC Summit in Male, the Maldives, last May,
member countries decided to establish the proposed South Asian
Free Trade Zone by the year 2001, four years ahead of the
previously scheduled time.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC Summit called on all member countries to accelerate
their cooperation in all fields and concentrate on economic
development in order to put an early end to the poverty and
backwardness of the region.
</P>
<P>
But Pakistan and India, the two largest economies within SAARC,
have never enjoyed the circumstances to do so.
</P>
<P>
Many believe that the targets set by the SAARC Summit may not
be achieved if the relationship between India and Pakistan remains
hostile.
</P>
<P>
Normalization of Pakistani-Indian relations is necessary for
strengthening peace and security in the region and for opening up
avenues of collaboration to tackle crucial economic issues.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that suppressed trade between Pakistan
and India strongly depresses the chances of promoting intra-SAARC
trade to its maximum potential.
</P>
<P>
Reviving and promoting bilateral trade between the two
countries through official channels is critical for sustained
expansion of mutually beneficial intra-SAARC trade and
trade-related joint ventures, they say.
</P>
<P>
As the two largest nations within SAARC, it is in the greater
interest of the two countries as well as the entire region that
Pakistan and India take concrete measures to liberalize their
trade to push forward cooperation within the SAARC towards the
next century.
</P>
<P>
There is no doubt that improvement of bilateral ties and the
signing of a no-war pact between Pakistan and India could make the
investment environment friendly in the region and attract more
foreign capital which is badly needed by the two countries in
developing their economies.
</P>
<P>
The international community is watching closely whether
Pakistan and India will be able to put their political disputes
aside for a while and negotiate issues including economic
cooperation in a serious and result-oriented manner.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Further Open Banking Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
looking at allowing the entry of more foreign banks on concerns
that existing banks are behaving as a cartel in charging lending
rates to customers, Business World reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said the move to further liberalize the banking
system was proposed by the Department of Finance and is part of
the reforms being drafted under the Philippines' long-term
development plan.
</P>
<P>
The country allowed 10 foreign banks to enter in 1995 as part
of its reforms to introduce competition in the industry and bring
down interest rates.
</P>
<P>
However, the banks failed to lower prime lending rates despite
the Central Bank's efforts in the financial crisis sweeping most
of Asia, prompting the Department of Finance to consider the new
proposal.
</P>
<P>
At Monday's auction, the interest rate of 91-day treasury bill,
the benchmark used by most banks to price their loans, surged
141.4 basis points to 18.18 percent from last week's level.
</P>
<P>
"Given the existing scenario, banks are behaving like
monopolies and they are squeezing their borrowers dry," a
government official said.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson said that he would meet
with the representatives of commercial banks Friday, encouraging
them to lower the prime lending rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Means of Recycling City Waste Introduced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have found
improved technology to deal with a problem which has caused
pollution and degradation of the environment, the "China Daily"
reported.
</P>
<P>
The technology, approved by the State Science and Technology
Commission(SSTC)last August, is designed to convert discharged
waste into useful and recyclable resources.
</P>
<P>
It was experimented in Guanghan, Sichuan Province, last August
and its use will expand to other urban areas in China, the
department for social development under the SSTC told China Daily
in an interview.
</P>
<P>
The use of the technology has yielded remarkable economic,
social and ecological results in Guangan, said Chen Congshun. Chen
is an official of the city's science and technology committee.
</P>
<P>
In the non-State-owned Guanghan Garbage Treatment Plant,
automatic separation is used to enable discharged waste to be
converted into organic compound fertilizers and plastic
products. The waste is used for heating and drying while producing
the fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
This technique means garbage can be made environmentally
friendly within 9-12 days, as opposed to the 40 days required for
burning garbage, said Wang Yingbin, the plant's manager.
</P>
<P>
The plant can treat 120 tons of garbage each day, converting 98
percent of it into useful resources.
</P>
<P>
The garbage recycling plant can earn 2.1 million yuan (253,000
US dollars) in profits each year from manufacturing organic
compound fertilizers and 400,000 yuan from plastic products.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang, after separating the garbage, the
manufacture and drying of organic compound fertilizers consumes
only one ton of coal each day, compared with five tons per day
without waste separation.
</P>
<P>
South and Southeast Asian countries, such as Thailand, India,
Singapore and Viet Nam, have also shown interest in the
technique.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuadoran Lawmaker Named Andean Parliament President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, December 8 (Xinhua) -- President of the National
Congress of Ecuador Heinz Moeller was appointed today as president
of the Andean Parliament for a two-year term, replacing outgoing
President Julio Cesar Turbay, a Colombian senator.
</P>
<P>
New vice presidents of the regional organization are Andres
Reggiardo Sayan from Peru, Felipe Montilla from Venezuela, Gonzalo
Valda Cardenas from Bolivia and Julio Cesar Turbay from Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Ecuadoran Gilberto Vaca, Tito Nilton Mendozas, Patricio Viteri
and Carlos Torres and Lourdes Espinoza were elected as members of
the permanent commissions of the Andean Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The 13th term of the parliament was installed today in Quito
and it would aims to integrate Andean countries and to analyze a
plan of legal reforms with the objective that the members of the
parliament be elected by direct vote.
</P>
<P>
At the inauguration of the first plenary session, the chief of
the Ecuadoran parliament delegation, Heinz Moeller, who is the
president of the Organizing Committee, welcomed legislators that
make up the Andean Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The agenda for the three-day meeting includes the election of
new leaders of the regional organization and an analysis on
a project for legal reforms designed to elect members of the
parliament through direct vote.
</P>
<P>
Moeller pointed out that the meeting is basic for the full
integration of Andean countries.
</P>
<P>
The Andean Community should make real the ideal of hero Simon
Bolivar, who fought in the 19th century for the independency of
the region from Spain, said Heinz Moeller.
</P>
<P>
In order to reach that goal, the countries should start to make
important changes in decentralization, administrative and
financial deregulation of public institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
