<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Employment Tops UK Agenda as EU President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The most important job for the
United Kingdom Presidency of the European Union (EU) for the first
half of 1998 would be to create more jobs, British Secretary of
State for Foreign Affairs Robin Cook said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Cook made the remark Monday afternoon in Brussels where he got
together with his EU counterparts to continue preparations for the
bloc's planned eastward enlargement ahead of an EU summit in
Luxembourg later this week.
</P>
<P>
After making a brief mention of jobs creation through education
and open market, the British foreign minister went on to call for
transparency of EU policies and institutions and "openness and
accessibility" of the EU through Internet.
</P>
<P>
He said the UK presidency would want to enhance the EU's fight
against organized crimes, particularly against drugs and computer
crimes.
</P>
<P>
He also said the EU presidency should assume the responsibility
for environment, adding that improvement of air quality was an
issue which deserved special attention.
</P>
<P>
On EU enlargement, Cook said that the "screening" of all the 11
applicants for EU membership would not slow down the EU's process
of negotiation with the six applicants in forefront -- the Czech
Republic, Hungary, Poland, Slovenia and the divided island of
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the EU's executive body, proposed in
July that the EU start talks with the six applicants which were
considered most advanced in economic and political reforms.
</P>
<P>
But this would leave the other five applicants -- Latvia,
Lithuania, Slovakia, Bulgaria and Romania -- in the EU's waiting
room.
</P>
<P>
The Luxembourg summit is expected to decide whether or not to
begin entry talks only with the six applicants on the fast lane or
with all the applicants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
