<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Economic Crisis Affects Canadian Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing Asian economic
crisis will slow down Canada's economic growth, with British
Columbia and Central Canada feeling the greatest effects,
according to a report released today by the Bank of Montreal.
</P>
<P>
The regions are most affected in Canada because of the exposure
to Asia of forest products, coal, base metals and the
transportation equipment and related sectors, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the economic growth prospects for Canada will be
reduced by 0.2 percentage points in 1998, it predicted.
</P>
<P>
Report attributes the impact to two main factors: a slowing in
growth in Asia and the appreciation of the Canadian dollar.
</P>
<P>
However, the report also noted that the Canadian financial
services sector could benefit from opportunities made available by
the reduced capabilities of Asian banks.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the crisis is likely to accelerate the opening up
of Japanese financial services markets, it said.
</P>
<P>
"The origins of the Asian crisis are found in a deadly mix of
overvalued currencies, large current account deficits and problems
loans in the banking systems," the report noted.
</P>
<P>
"A long-term solution will require substantial structural
reform of the banking systems and the individual economies," it
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
