<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Higher Against Yen, Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar rose against
the Japanese yen and German mark Monday on the news that Japan was
not prepared to intervene in the currency market to support the
weakening yen.
</P>
<P>
The yen was pushed higher in a quiet trading today with no
fresh economic news, and Eisuke Sakakibara, Japan's vice finance
minister for international affairs, declining to comment on
foreign-exchange levels.
</P>
<P>
In New York, the dollar finally settle at 130.45 yen, up from
130.20 late Friday. The dollar has not been so high since May
1992.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also settled at 1.7893 marks, up from 1.7830, to
reach its highest level since October 21.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday:
1.4579 Swiss francs, up from 1.4400; 5.9863 French francs, up from
5.9641; 1,752 Italian lire, up from 1,744; and 1.4231 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.4238.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6483 U.S. dollars, down from
1.6573 U.S. dollars.  
</P>
