<HEADLINE> 30 Islamic Leaders Arrive in Tehran for OIC Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 8 (Xinhua) -- So far 30 leaders of Islamic
countries have arrived in Tehran to attend the eighth Islamic
Summit to be opened Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The leaders included two emirs, two crown princes, 16
presidents, three vice presidents and seven prime ministers.
</P>
<P>
The emirs are Kuwaiti Emir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah and
Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin Khalifa Al-Thani, and the two crown
princes are Saudi Arabia's Adbullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz and Jordan's
Hassan Ibn Talal.
</P>
<P>
The presidents are Syrian President Hafez al-Assad, Turkish
President Suleyman Demirel, Lebanese President Elias Hrawi,
Sudanese President Omar Hassan Ahmad al-Bashir, Azerbaijani
President Geidar Aliyev, Mozambican President Joaquim Alberto
Chissano.
</P>
<P>
There were also Benin President Mathieu Kerekou, Chad President
Idriss Deby, Sierra Leonean President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, Guinean
President Lansana Conte.
</P>
<P>
Earlier arrivals included Senegalese President Abdou Diouf,
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat, Turkmen President Saparmurat
Niyazov, Tajik President Emomali Rakhmonov, Maldivian President
Maumoon Abdul Gayoom and Mali President Alpha Oumar Konare.
</P>
<P>
Among vice-presidents were Abdul-Halim Khaddam of Syria, Taha
Yassin Ramadan of Iraq and Major General Abdo Rabo Mansour Hadi
of Yemen.
</P>
<P>
Prime ministers arrived included Mahathir Bin Mohammad of
Malaysia, Nawaz Sharif of Pakistan, Abdul-Salam Majali of Jordan,
Abdul Latif Al-Filali of Morocco, Sheikh Hasina of Bangladesh,
Rafik Hariri of Lebanon and Hama Amadou of Niger.
</P>
<P>
President of Afghanistan Burhanuddin Rabbani was invited to the
meeting as an observer, since the OIC had decided to leave the
official seat of his country vacant.
</P>
<P>
Other dignitaries to arrive before Tuesday's summit include
Bahraini Foreign Minister Sheikh Mohammad bin Mubarak Al-Khalifa,
Foreign Minister Rashid Abdullah AL-Nuaimi of the United Arab
Emirates and Ugandan Deputy Prime Minister Paul Orono Etiang.
</P>
