<HEADLINE> UN Chief Satisfied With Iraqi Decision on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the
United Nations Kofi Annan said here today he is not surprised
Iraq has agreed to carry out the third phase of the oil-for-food
deal, the Kuwaiti News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The deal is of great help to the Iraqis, and "I am happy for
them that the Iraqi government has made the decision," Annan said
at the Kuwait airport during a stopover en route to Iranian
capital Tehran to attend the summit of the Organization of Islamic
Conference.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.N. is doing whatever possible to make sure
that "the operation is run effectively and smoothly."
</P>
<P>
"The (U.N. Security) Council has never targeted the people of
Iraq. If the intention was to punish the people of Iraq, we would
have never had the oil-for-food scheme," he concluded.
</P>
<P>
Iraq Monday agreed to cooperate with the U.N. Security Council
to extend the deal for another period of six months.
</P>
<P>
This implied a change of Iraq's position on this question since
it has said that it will not implement the deal until the
contracts signed during the first two phases have been
accomplished.
</P>
<P>
A Security Council resolution adopted in 1995 allows the
sanctions-ridden Iraq to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil
over every six months and to buy food and medicines. It was put
into effect a year ago and the third phase was set to start last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were imposed after Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in
1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
