<HEADLINE> Government Reshuffled in Cameroun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, December 8 (Xinhua) -- A new coalition government
came into being in Cameroun late Sunday night with Peter Mafany
Musonge retaining his post as prime minister, Radio Cameroun
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Camerounian President Paul Biya signed a presidential decree
announcing the formation of a government of national unity, which
is composed of 28 ministries and 47 members.
</P>
<P>
Bello Bouba, president of leading opposition, the National
Union for Democracy and Progress (NUDP), also joined the new
government and becomes the minister of state in charge of
industrial and commercial development.
</P>
<P>
Amadou Ali, former secretary-general at the presidency, was
appointed as defense minister while Kontchou Kouomegni, former
minister of state in charge of communication, becomes the
minister of state in charge of external relations.
</P>
<P>
Newly created are three ministries, namely the ministry of
towns, the ministry of public investment and regional development
and the ministry of employment, labor and social insurance.
</P>
<P>
Former ministry of social and women's affairs was split into
two ministries -- the ministry of social affairs and the ministry
of women's affairs.
</P>
<P>
The reshuffle of the government of national unity came over 30
days after Biya was sworn in on November 3. He won the
presidential elections on October 12, 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
