<HEADLINE> Turkey Defends Its Military Ties With Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Defense Minister Ismet
Sezgin today reiterated that the Turkish-Israeli military
cooperation is not directed at any third party, the Anatolia News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Sezgin, also deputy prime minister, made the remarks prior to a
meeting with his Israeli counterpart Yitzhak Mordechai, who
arrived here today on a three-day visit, the first visit to Turkey
by an Israeli defense minister.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Turkey and Israel are two important countries in
the region, Sezgin said that their cooperation will contribute to
peace and stability of the region.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to say once again that the military cooperation
between us is not directed against any other countries," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Sezgin expressed the belief that Mordechai's visit to Ankara
is bound to further strengthen friendship and cooperation between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Mordechai said that the Turkish-Israeli
cooperation is of strategic significance to the region, saying he
will discuss with Turkish leaders some issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
The rapidly expanding Turkish-Israeli military alliance aroused
severe uneasiness among the Arab countries, which have repeatedly
urged Ankara to stop this sort of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel signed a defense industry pact and a
military training agreement last year, laying a foundation for
their cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai also met with Turkish Chief of General Staff Ismail
Hakki Karadayi today. They exchanged views on cooperation between
the two armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have agreed in principle on joint production of
long-range missiles, according to sources close to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Turkey has been planning to purchase
Israeli-made missiles.
</P>
<P>
A high-ranking Turkish military delegation is to visit Israel
next January to discuss the details of this project, reliable
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli defense minister will also hold talks with Turkish
Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz and Parliament Speaker Hikmet Cetin
during his visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, Mexico Sign Accord on Economic Partnership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) and
Mexico here today signed an accord on economic partnership,
political coordination and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The so-called Global Accord was signed Monday by Mexican
Foreign Minister Angel Gurria, foreign ministers from the 15 EU
member countries and Manuel Marin, vice-president of the European
Commission, the EU's executive body.
</P>
<P>
Marin said at the signing ceremony that the accord opened a
"privileged relationship" between the two sides which were urged
to develop the "indispensable" political and economic ties in
order to face the future in the best possible conditions.
</P>
<P>
An interim accord on commerce and accompanying issues was also
signed Monday by the two sides in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
The global accord aims to institutionalize the political
dialogue, reinforce the commercial and economic relations by means
of "bilateral and preferential, progressive and reciprocal
liberalization of exchanges" according to WTO rules and strengthen
and enlarge their cooperation.
</P>
<P>
A joint council, which has been established to supervise the
implementation of the accord, will examine all the major issues
concerning the accord and all other bilateral and international
issues of common interest.
</P>
<P>
The EU notes that respect of both democratic principles and
fundamental human rights also constitute an essential part of the
accord.
</P>
<P>
The formal relations between the EU and Mexico began with a
cooperation accord signed in 1975, which was aimed to develop the
economic and commercial relations between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation accord was replaced by another accord signed in
Luxembourg in April 1991, which extended the domain of their
bilateral cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971209.0290 </DOCNO>
