<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Shares up on Swiss Merger Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Leading stock markets in Europe
all surged higher Monday and ended firmer, boosted by news of two
Swiss banks' merger, dollar's strength and Wall Street's rally on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Britain's leading shares closed at an eight-week high at
5,187.4, up 44.50 points although Wall Street's dull start today
loosened the FTSE 100 index's grip on the 5,200-point level.
</P>
<P>
The 35 billion pounds (57.4 billion U.S. dollars) merger
between Union Bank of Switzerland (UBS) and Swiss Bank Corp (SBC)
dominated the headlines in the City, which focused attention on
the domestic takeover scene and buoyant financial and banking
sectors.
</P>
<P>
News of the merger deal helped renew speculative interest in
British banks.
</P>
<P>
German shares in Frankfurt ended 53.28 points higher with the
DAX-30 index closing at 4,223.36.
</P>
<P>
Bank shares also surged on news of the two Swiss banking
giants' merger.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 index in Paris finished up 22.38 points at 2,932.47.
Dealers said that shares were cheered by the dollar's rally, Wall
Street's gains on Friday and positive news involving French blue
chip companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
